\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-490\li518\ri0\sa240\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin518\itap0\pararsid1003219 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Can you tell me a bit about the house, what sort of size was it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Well - it was immediately above Carl's the fruit shop. Number {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}
}two Nith Place{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} was the address. And - we had - a kitchen. And a parlour. A kitchen and a parlour, and upstairs there was three bedrooms.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 That was quite a big house then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Mm hm. And of course there was eleven of us. We needed the - yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 How did you get into it, was there a passage?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 
You went - no, this was a - the door opened out on to the street. You went up then a stair. And there was two houses - up the stairway. The other house was occupied a - a Philip Burns. He had an aerated water business down in the 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceName}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Dock{\*\xmlclose} {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceType}}Park{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
. Now that now is a cycle shop I think, and it was next door to where Armstrong Dick is. There the water works were. That was Burns. So we lived together and we were good neighbours.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 How about toilets, did you have to share a toilet with them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 No, we had our own toilet. We had our own toilet, there was nothing shared.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 What about a bathroom?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Oh there was no bathroom. Oh no, no bathrooms in those days. Just the toilet.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 At that time there was no one else living with you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Oh no. No, it was a family house. A family house.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Did your mother have anybody to help her in the house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 No. No. Not - the - the girls never went out at night, when they come home from their work that was them in for the night.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 They would give her a hand then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 
And - yes. They were dressmakers and shop assistants. And the dressmakers they said - sat and - they did their dressmaking at home, not for outsiders, for themselves.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 And presumably for you younger children? Did they make things for you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Not for me. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Where would your clothes come from?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Oh - they were bought, they must have been bought, because - a brother that was older than me and th
ere was two elder brothers, but the one that was - older than me was about - you know, he was a - he'd be about ten years older than me. Perhaps not quite ten but - his clothes didn't fit me. So it was not a shared, it - it was not a case of handing down.
 No, our clothes were bought.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 What about boots and shoes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 
Well, we wore boots. We'd no shoes, it was boots. And - I can remember - one Christmas, my sister May and I went up town, and we were only kids at the time, to buy mothera Christmas presen
t. And I come back with a tin of boot blacking, great big tin of boot blacking, and my sister had a small bag, a penny bag of chocolate beans, that was our Christmas to our mother.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 One useful and one luxury?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Well - the blacking was different fro
m the present day polish. You had to wet the brush and - dip it in the blacking, and then put - apply it wet to the leather, and you'd to polish for ever and a day until it dried, but you got a lovely shine when it dried.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 That's like the old Army spit and polish?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 
It would probably be the same, aye. Different from the present day polishes altogether, it took, you a long while. I mean there was no - no - shoes or boots allowed to be cleaned on the Sunday.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Were they all done on Saturday night?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 
Everything was done on a Saturday night. The newspapers were put away - under the cushion of the chair, you weren't allowed to look at a newspaper on the Sunday.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 To go back to cleaning shoes, did you have any jobs to do in the house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 No.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Did you get off with it because you were the baby or because you were a boy?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Probably because I was a boy.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 You think your brothers got off with it as well?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Oh yes. I used to clean - help clean the knives and forks. Now - we had a knif
e board. That was a - a long wooden board that was set up on the - table in the scullery, and - you used - bath brick, what they called bath brick. A brown - brown - a brown powdery substance, and you rubbed the forks and the knives on that. For a minute 
or two. And then you rubbed them up with a polishing cloth. And then some hot water and washed them and put them back in the drawer. I did that quite - quite frequently. Polished knives and forks.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 What about going messages, would you do that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Yes
. I did a lot of messages. Mother went out too and did her own shopping. But - I used to go with her - and carry the bags. And of course I was always there with a purpose in mind. That was - what I was going to get from the shopkeepers.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Not from your mother?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 
No, no, oh no, from the shopkeepers. Robert Johnson was the family grocer, that was - in the High Street, their shop was further down - nearer Ewans the Jewellers in those days. And - old Robert Johnson that was the owner of the business, he 
always - tore a piece of paper off - butter paper or ham paper, and made a poke and - turned round the back and he had a - wooden drawer in the press, bring it down, half a dozen mixtures, dolly mixtures - in the poke, that was for me. Well now I was as p
roud as a peacock when I got that from him.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 So it wasn't really to help your mother?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 It was - to try and see what they - I could get. I knew the shops where I got them. Rewards. And -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Do you think all the children that went in would get that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Was it just some people?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 
No. Mother was a good customer you see, she'd a big household to keep going. But then again it might not be a big household in those days. It was an average family.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 To go back to clothes were all your clothes new? Your mother wouldn't get second hand ones maybe?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 No. Everything was bought, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 That would be an expense for you all. How about washing? Did your mother wash at home?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Or did she send things out?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 No, she washed 
at home. She'd a big tub, and it sat on a - on a stool. A large stood, in the kitchen. A big wooden one. And the water was boiled - on the fire, and brought through into the tub, and the clothes were all put in the tube. Now we'd no drying green. At this 
place. The clothes were all dried in the house.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 That must have been a problem?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 
Well - it - I think that they were dried off in the parlour. You never were allowed in the parlour unless there was some - somebody special calling.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 You lived in the kitchen?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Lived in the kitchen. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 What size of room was it, it must have been a fair size?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 It was. It was a big kit - it - it was a big room. Well - you can judge it because - it would be the size - roughly of Carol's shop down the r
oad. Because our kitchen was over his back shop. And the parlour was over the front shop. So it was a fair size.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 How about your father, did he help your mother about the house or did he feel as they had six daughters she had plenty of help?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Oh -
 there was no question of any of the - the males - helping in the house, My father was a great fiddler. He played the violin and - I can remember them at night, after he got his tea - he'd go up to his bedroom and sit and play his violin - for maybe an ho
ur or so.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Did he go out and play at night?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 No, no. No, that was only his own entertainment. He - that he played the violin.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 What about bringing up coal and so on?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Well we - we -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Would he help with that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 No, the coalmen who brought the coals.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 You kept the coal upstairs?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 
No, we - we'd no outside accommodation at all. Nothing at all. With no drying green or anything like that. You came from the street up to the house and that was your accommodation, and the coals wer
e put - I think there was a coal cellar. I wouldn't like to be certain of it. But there would be a cellar, there must have been a cellar in the house. Somewhere to keep the coal. I'll tell you where it was, it was under the stairs. The cellar. The stairs 
up to the bedrooms. And the coal cellar was underneath that. That was it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 So your mother wouldn't have to run up and down stairs to fetch it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 No, no, no, nothing like that. She had everything at her hand.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Did your father do very much with you children when you were small?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 
No. No you see - he was away out first thing in the morning. And you didn't see him - until teatime. He come in about teatime. And as I say after he got his tea - he went up and played his violin. and by the time he ca
me down - we children were away to bed.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 So it would really just be at weekends that you saw him?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Well we saw him daily. But - only for a short time. Because - he got all his food out where he was working in the bake}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16396100\charrsid7372706 -}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 house you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Didn't he come home for any meals?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 He didn't come home for any meals, no. He went out in the morning and came back at night when the job - when the day's job was finished.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 What about Sundays then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 No Sunday work. Oh -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Would he do anything with you children on Sundays?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 
Well we were paraded to the - church there, the elder children were paraded to the church every Sunday morning. And we children went to the Sunday school. We come home and we - we had our dinner. Was dinner in those days, n
ot lunch. It was our dinner, and - we were taken for a walk in the afternoon, I can always remember. Father and mother and the younger children, were taken for a walk around the Mile House. And when we got to the Mile House we each got a black string ball
. One.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Make it last 'til you got home?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 That was because we went the walk with them.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 That was quite a fair distance?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Well it - it would be a mile both ways from the - town. Two miles. But you thought nothing of walking in those days.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 It was the done thing to go for walks Sunday afternoon?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 
Yes. Well that was the Sunday afternoon we put in, for to walk round the Mile House. Never varied. Around the Mile House on the Sunday afternoon. Father and mother, and - I think it was my si
ster and I. The sister that was nearest my age. Four of us. And - I can remember a - the bag of black striped balls was produced and we each got one. No more than one.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Would your father ever take you out on your own?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Not that I remember.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 You just remember going out with your mother and your sister?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 With my mother and sister, aye.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 
How about your big brothers and sisters, would they help you much when you were small, like dressing you and putting you to bed and this sort of thing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 
Yes, I suppose they did - they - my sisters - saw me to bed at night, I can remember that. They saw me to bed. But - apart from that - I can't remember any - them doing anything for me at all.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Did you have to go to bed at a certain time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Oh yes. Yes, we - away to bed - about seven o'clock at night I was away to bed.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Presumably you would have to share a bed or a bedroom with somebody?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 My brother.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Just the one?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Well the other brother was away then. Aye, he was away. But I was with my other brother, the two of us.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 And presumably all your sisters were in one of the other rooms?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Yes. Mm hm.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 And your parents?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 And my parents had the third bedroom. Mm hm.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Nobody had to sleep in the kitchen in your house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 
Now wait a moment. I think there was a bed in the kitchen. Or am I mixing it up with the Brooms Road House. I know the brooms Road house had a bed in the kitchen, there was a bed recess in the kitchen. But I - I - I really couldn't tell you - whe
ther there was a bed - in the kitchen - or not. I couldn't honestly say.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 You say your sisters generally put you to bed?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Uh huh.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Do you remember how old you were when you started to go all by yourself?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Well I was put the bed all the time we lived at {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Nith Place
{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}. And I would be about nine. Nine when my father died. And we left {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Nith Place{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} shortly after. But at 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Brooms Road{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} - I was on my own. Mm hm.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 How about baths?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 No baths at all.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 You didn't have a tin bath in your kitchen?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 No. So far as I can remember, I never got a bath.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Just a wash down?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Just a wash down at the sink. And you'd to watch your turn.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 It must have been awkward?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Mm hm. Mm hm. There was no baths. And you'd to wait until the girls - g
ot their wash and out the road before you were allowed in to wash. But - that was just a - they washed at the sink.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 How about clean clothes, like vests and pants and whatnot, would you get them regularly?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Oh yes. Mother washed every week.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 You would get clean clothes once a week?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Yes. Yes. Aye. But - I can't remember ever having a bath as a kid.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 A lot of people had tin baths in front of the fire.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Yes. No, we - we had nothing. But I might have got a bath in the tub. But - I can't recollect it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 How about eating? You would all eat in the kitchen?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 
That's right. Yes. And - we hadn't sufficient chairs to go round - and I remember some of my sisters that sat on boxes. They had their own box. And they set the box on end.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 They'd get that from the fruit shop?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Yes. There'd probably be an apple box or something of the sort. But we - I can remember that. There was three a side.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Did you all eat at once?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Yes. When we were - were there. Well that's what I said,
 we had the boxes. And put three a side, well that was six and - there'd probably be two at either end. Something like that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Did you ever eat in the parlour at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Not to my knowledge, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 When you were in there it was just for sitting?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 It was for - visitors.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Not for eating?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 
I - I had my first photograph there, I - I was going to have a look at it to see if I could find it, when I was a small boy. The photograph was taken and I can remember the incident quite well, standin
g on a chair, and it was - Peter Burn from next door - that took the photograph.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 In the parlour?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 In the parlour. But -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 That's the sort of occasion it was used for?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 That's right, no day - nobody was allowed in the parlour unless - there was visitors there or something like that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Did your mother have to cook on the fire?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 
She had a - a coal oven - in the kitchen. There was a - the fireplace and then down the right hand side was the oven, with two or three shelves, and down at t
he bottom - yes, down at the bottom was a fire box. And she put - the coal into the firebox, and heated the oven, and she cooked in that. We'd no - we'd no - gas grills or anything like that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 No other ways of cooking apart from coal?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 When was breakfast eaten, father would be away out?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Oh he was away five or six o'clock of the morning.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Do you think your mother would get up to see him out?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 No, no. No, no, he'd do it himself. Well the girls started work at eight o'clock. So
 they must have had their breakfast about half past seven. And then - we would come down about eight o'clock probably. For school. Second sitting.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Can you remember what you used to get for your breakfast?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 We never had a - a cooked breakfast exce
pt on Sunday morning. Sunday morning was bacon and egg. Always. But the rest of the week it was a plain breakfast. Bread and butter. You didn't get bread and butter and jam.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Not even porridge?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 And a cup of tea?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 A cup of tea. Cup of tea and bread and butter, or bread and jam. But you didn't get butter and jam.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 How about dinner time? Presumably when you were at school you would come home for your dinner?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Well, we were all home - the girls - they - they'd get out at one o'
clock. I don't know about the girls that worked in the shop, they must have got away about one o'clock too, but because so far as I can remember we all fed at the same time.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Except father?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Oh yes, he was out, eh was away at his work.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Did you have a good dinner then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Yes. You'd soup. You'd soup every day. And you had a meat - a meat course, and a pudding afterward. But you didn't get tea.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 That really was your main meal of the day?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 That's right. Tea - I remember I used to get 
the top of my - my dad's egg. That was what I got. The top of the egg. He had the - he had the remainder. But I got the top of the egg - teatime.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 What else would you have for tea?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 We only got - a cake at the weekend. We got a sugar cookie. A - a
 ha'penny cake. Not a cake, a cake was a penny I think. More the - buns, fancy buns. You got one of these - on - was it a Sunday, Sunday for your tea. That was the only day in the week we had cakes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 What did you have other days for your tea?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Bread. Bread and butter. Or jam. Mm hm.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 You didn't have any cakes for teatime?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 No cake, no, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Would your father not bring home cakes and buns for you?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 He was a bread baker. He only made - he only made the bread. But - he never brought anything home.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 He couldn't bring anything out of the shop for you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 No, no. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 You would think that would have been one of the perks of a job like that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Oh there were - perks were unknown at that time.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Obviously your mother wouldn't need to make her own bread?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 No, but she baked scones. She was a good baker, add baked the scones. But no bread. Nothing fancy, just scones.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 How about jam, did she make her own jam?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 I suppose she would. Because we never - we never boug
ht jam to my knowledge. What we used to - to do was - we had a two pound jam pot, and we used to go to the grocers on a Saturday morning, and you got one filled with treacle and the other filled with syrup for a penny a time. That was bulk syrup and bulk 
treacle, in two pound jams.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 It came out of a big barrel or something?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Yes. That was a Saturday morning - message I used to do.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 But you had jam as well sometimes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Oh we had jam, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Did your mother ever make pickles or that sort of thing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 No. We never - we were never that type. Family. No,
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 How about making beer?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Oh no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 And wines?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 No, I don't think drink ever was in the house.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 What about medicines, some people made their own medicines.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang1034\langfe1033\langnp1034\insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang1034\langfe1033\langnp1034\insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang1034\langfe1033\langnp1034\insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 No. No. No. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 
Not - not us - not us. I can't remember ever having medicine as a kid. But it would be castor oil, that would be the main - that would be the main medicine.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 You wouldn't be able to grow your own vegetables and fruit?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 No garden.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 For pickling or bottling or anything like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 No, we'd no garden.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 You would be quite handy having the fruit shop down below though?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 We'd no money to spend at the fruit shop.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 You would need vegetables for the soup and things like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Well, we - I suppose - mother would go down herself.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Do you ever remember her using tins of food?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 We never had tinned food, I can remember the first time - I tasted tinned fruit
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 When was that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 It was when we lived in Brooms Road, we
 lived next door to a family called - Moran, Sam Moran had a fish shop - in St Michaels Street. And I used to go - messages at the shop, and this day - I was invited down, they had a week}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16396100\charrsid7372706 -}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 house at the Quay - Glencaple, and I was invited down for the day, a
nd when I went down I remember - it was - sliced pineapple was the tinned fruit, and that was the first time I'd ever seen - anything of the sort. And - oh I didn't go - and I didn't like it at all. No. I didn't like it, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 It would be a strange fruit for you wouldn't it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 It was something new. And I didn't take to it and - that would be about 1912. That I - that my first - meeting with tinned - food.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Did you get meat every day, or were there days when you didn't have any meat?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 No, we'
d meat every day. And on a Friday night - there was a - a butchers shop, David Milligan, I mentioned that in the - in my - report there, he got the offal in}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16396100\charrsid7372706  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 from the slaughterhouse, they killed on the Thursday. For the weekend - shopping. And you used to go on the Friday night to David Milligan and you got a big paper - of liver - for three}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid16396100\charrsid7372706  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 pence. Now you consider the price of liver at the present day. You got a great big paper full for three}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid16396100\charrsid7372706  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 pence.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 I suppose it wouldn't keep, that they would need to get rid of it quickly?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 
Well that if they only killed once a week, and that was Thursday end of the week. There again - my first experience of frozen meat - funny how things sti}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16396100\charrsid7372706 c}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 k in your mind. There was a butchers shop in the High Street, Eastman}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16396100\charrsid7372706 \rquote }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 s. 
And all that they sold was frozen - mutton. And the sheep carcasses all used to hang around, and I used to look at it and wonder - how in the name of goodness did that keep all the way from Australia or New Zealand where it come from. And that was the onl
y meat they sold, frozen meat. Mutton.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Was that quite a cheap meat in those days?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 
Oh it was very cheap, but I couldn't tell you the prices, I wasn't interested in the price. But - the average - the average - housewife passed it by. She didn't think it was - it was good to eat. The ordinary, the home meat, you bought the home meat.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 You wouldn't be in the way of getting extra things like rabbits from poaching?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 No, no. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 There was always enough food in your house to go round?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Oh yes. There was never any - any scarcity. Every thing was plain, there was nothing fancy. But - you always had as much as you wanted.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 At mealtimes were you allowed to talk?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 There was no restriction on it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Some people bring their children up to eat and not speak?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Aye, oh no, I - I think we would all talk a - we'd all be talking at meal times
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Could you choose what you wanted to eat, were you allowed to leave any bits on your plates?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 No. You didn't choose, it was put in front
 of you. And if you didn't eat it up it was produced at the next meal. And you had to eat that before you were allowed anything else.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 And if you wanted more what happened?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Well you couldn't have more. That was your share and that was the end of it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 It was all just divided out?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Were you expected to hold your knife and fork a certain way?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 No. No. You used your knife and fork, you - probably were shown - how to used it, and that was the end of it. There's no question of l
aying it back on the plate when you were finished.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Would you be allowed to read at the table?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Or bring toys with you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Oh no. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 You were there to eat and that was that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 That was right.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 When could you leave the table, could you leave when you were finished or did you have to wait 'til everybody was done?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 There was no rule, I think you could leave when you - had your meal.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 You would have to ask permission?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 No, you - just left the table. Mm hm. Free and easy in that respect.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Was it always your mother who would dish the food out?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Even when father was there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Yes, she dished everything, yes. He didn't interfere in any way.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Did she dish out in any special order? If father was there did he get his first?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Oh he would always get his first.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Was it done by ages after that, or did the boys get served first?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 I don't know that was any particular rule, after father got his good then the - the - the rest of got it in 
turn, and presumably the youngest got it last.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Can you remember having a birthday when you were small?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Never had a birthday party, nor you got a birthday on your - a present on your birthday.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 You didn't get anything at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 No. What actually what happened - there was a - a spiced treacle pudding was made on your birthday.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 A dumpling?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Dumpling. And that was - that was your birthday.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 You would do quite well then if there were nine of you to have birthdays throughout the year?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Well of course you - you never looked on it as anything special like that, it -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 You didn't make a thing about it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 I don't know that the - the - the elder - members of the family - got the - pudding on their birthday, it was only the y
oung - the younger ones. They got this steam pudding, a treacle pudding.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 How about Christmas? Would you make more of a fuss at Christmas?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 No. We - we - we had no money - at Christmas. You had no - no money to spend. You hung up your stocking at 
Christmas. And - you got an apple and an orange. And a toy. That was all you got - at Christmas.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Was there a special Christmas dinner?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Nothing like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 No.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Would your father be working on Christmas Day?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Don't think so. But - oh no, certain none of them - worked on a Christmas - Day, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Can you remember what sort of toys you got, were they just small things?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 I'm trying to remember. Oh they were only -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Were you ever taken out visiting neighbours or friends or relations?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 No. We'd no friends or relatives.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 No friends even?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 No. We never went visiting.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Your mother didn't have any -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 No contacts with outside the family circle.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 And your family circle was fairly limited?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 The house.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Just your immediate family?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Mm hm. No, we never went visiting. And we never had any - body that visited us. We lived our own lives, in our own way.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Do you think there was any reason for that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 No, it was just a way of living. L
ike we - we never made - what - like - they spoke to the neighbours, but it never developed to the extent of visiting.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Not a case of popping in and out?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 No, no. No. We had no time for that. Everybody was fully occupied with their own way of life
, and - you wouldn't think of doing entertaining. We'd no money to entertain.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 You can understand that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Mm hm.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 You wouldn't see grandparents at all really did you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 No. I never saw any grand - father or mother. Never seen them. Aunts and uncles yes. But nothing beyond that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Did you visit your aunts and uncles?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Well - they - they - you may think it's funny, they visited us maybe once a year or so. But - as for us visiting them no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Do you think there were too many of you to go?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Well we'd no money to go. The first time I visited my aunt in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Edinburgh{\*\xmlclose}
, I was on my way - from the - Royal Flying Corps up to Dundee to join my regiment, and I stopped off at {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Edinburgh{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
, and I had a wee while to wait and I went along and saw my aunt. Now that's the one and only time I recollect having visited my aunt.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 You said you used to go out shopping with your mother?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 You never really went out with your father much at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 He was - only there - well - apart from working in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Dumfries{\*\xmlclose}
 to - latterly, he got a job away from town. And he was only in the - he was only home - occasional weekends.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 So you won't really remember a great deal about him at all then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Not going shopping or anything, no, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Can you tell me about any other outings you might have had, like picnics?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 
The only - the only holiday or outing I ever got was a Sunday school trip once a year. That was the one and only time - I got away - from home.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Did the whole family go on the trip?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Oh no. Just - me, I was at Sunday school. And my sister, she would probably go too, when she was at Sunday school.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 The younger one?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Mm hm. But - that was the only holiday - that we ever had.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Some people used to go down to the Quay on Sundays.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 
Oh no. No, there was nothing like that with us. Sunday - was a holy day in the true sense of the word. You never ventured - anything like that, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Did anybody else in the house manage to get away for a holiday at all, some of your older sisters when they were working maybe?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 
Later on - they used to go away, they got a fortnights holiday. And they would go to always Kippford. They went down to Kippford and - we probably had a day to go down and see them during the fortnight. My mother and myself.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 How old would you be then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 
Ah well I'd be getting, I'd be - ten or twelve. Not in my early days, that was in the - the later years. That would be about 1912. Or something like that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 How about Saturdays, can you tell me what you did on Saturdays? I know you took your father's breakfast up.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 
A - apart from that, that was the only job that I can remember doing on a Saturday morning, we just played around. Was plenty of kids of my own age, and - we just played - round the {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceName}}Dock{\*\xmlclose} 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceType}}Park{\*\xmlclose} or down at the {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Ness{\*\xmlclose} at the waters side.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Played football, this sort of thing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 I didna play football, no, but we played games - other games.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 What sort of games did you play, can you remember any of them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Aye - there was - smout, that was with the three - three holes, three holes dug in the groun}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid16396100\charrsid7372706 d}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 
 and - you played with a marble, knock them down, knock them down, three times, and then you lined - the small coloured marbles against the wall and you bounced your big ball - against 
the wall and you gradually advanced and you - the - the - game was to try and hit these stanies as we called them, the small ones. And you kept as many as you - and if you let your own - marble fall that was your turn finished. Your opponent took his turn
 then. And that was with marbles. Summertime - occasionally - we went with - Mr Burns's boy on the lorry, that was the lemon}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16396100\charrsid7372706 a}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 
de lorry.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Going out delivering?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Selling. And that was - out for an hour or so and back in. Then - I had another play - there was a bakers shop, 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Murray}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16396100\charrsid7372706 {\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}\rquote }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 s, up in 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Galloway Street{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}. And I knew this fellow {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Cairns{\*\xmlclose}
{\*\xmlclose}, David Cairns, and he had a two wheel barrow on which he might have - two or three boards of bread. And this was him - out selling. That was - before the days of vans. Th
e barrow. And - the bread was covered with - sacks. And - I used to go and help him - up the hill with the barrow. That used to be an afternoons job. Doing his rounds with him.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Did you get paid for these things?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Oh no. No, no. I knew the boy. A
nd it was only done to help him. It was a load - he might have - what, five or six dozen loaves on his barrow. And you pulled the barrow - from {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Gulliver Street{\*\xmlclose}
{\*\xmlclose} in Marshaltown - right up as far as {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceName}}Johnson{\*\xmlclose} {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceType}}Park{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
. That was about the limit - of his journey.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Still quite a way to go though?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 
Oh it was a - it was a way and it was up hill all the way. Ah well that - that - don't know - where we had - any games. We never played football. You've to go down to the Kingholm in those days if you wanted to play 
football. You played football down there, but I never had any - notion of football.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Did you wear different clothes on a Saturday or was it just your weekday clothes you wore?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Well I think all that we had was our weekday clothes and our best clothes for Sunday. One change. That was all then.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 You had to keep yourself clean on Sundays?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 If you fell in the water as happened periodically you just had to stay in - until your clothes were dry.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 If things like that happened you wouldn't be allowed to put on your Sunday things?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 
Oh no. No, no. No, you - either went to bed and - stayed there until your clothes were dried or - if they weren't too bad, you just made them do. But you weren't allowed in your Sunday clothes until Sunday.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Did you have special clothes then like stiff collars, this sort of thing for Sundays? What would you wear on a Sunday?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 I - I wore - a stiff collar - but it - it would probably be about - four or five inches long, fitted round your neck. Just the same
 - the same idea as a soft collar, only it was stiff. And you went those collars - they were sent to the laundry to be done up. But - that was the - the - the - the collar, we wore the collar and our Sunday suit. There was nothing - nothing fancy about it
. We - later on we got the cellular collars, when they - when they came on the market later on, we used to get the cellular collar, you simply washed those yourself.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Much easier to look after?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Mm hm. But the linen ones, you had to have them starched.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Which church did you go to?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Greyfriars?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 That's just the ordinary Church of Scotland?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Yes, Presbyterian.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 How often did you go to church, I know you went at least once on a Sunday?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Our parents went every Sunday, but we 
went to Sunday school. We didn't - we didn't go to church and Sunday school, no - the Sunday school was after the church service. But - we didn't go to church, we simply went to the Sunday school. Occasionally we went to church if there was anything speci
al on in the way of - services. Flower services or Easter or Christmas services, we'd go to the church then but normally - the Sunday school was - was all on the Sunday
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 How did you go on the Sunday school trip, did you go on -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Train. Walked to th
e station. We walked to the - formed up at - Reverse Hall and marched down to the station. With a cup - fastened to our - lapel of our coat, you used to take your own cup.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Did you have a label on as well?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 No. And - Provost Mogerley, I don't know
 whether you knew - you knew that family - they lived down then - they had pork butchers business. He supplied sausage rolls and pies. Can remember that. And when you went to the field you sit down and - you got - your cup of tea, it was tea, and a sausag
e roll and a pie. And I think you got a cake. A bun. Not a cake, a bun. And the - that was provided by the Sunday school, and if you needed anything else to eat well - you provided it yourself.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 You would stay all day?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Well, we - you - you'd leav
e about ten o'clock in the morning. Lochanhead was a - a favourite rendezvous we used to go for our Sunday school picnic just in the fields. We parked ourself in the field and there was games. Arranged. And you had games. But by the time you got - to Loch
anhead and got sat down and - got your meal you were well on into the afternoon. And about four o'clock you'd be starting to gather your things together and form up for the return journey.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Did you have races and so on?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Races, just the usual - sports for the kids.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Sunday school trips haven't changed all that much?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 No. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Did you go to any other things that the church organised? Were you a member of the choir or anything like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 No. No, nothing at all. No, that - as a matter of fact - I disappe}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16396100\charrsid7372706 a}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 
red from church circles - round about - what about 19 - 14. I don't know what happened but - just - there was nobody there to push you out, and we just went our own ways and - the church was a thing of the past. 'Cos that I}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid16396100\charrsid7372706  remember - when I went to join}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 
 the Royal Flying Corps as a volunteer you had to get - two adults signatures, one of which - was reckoned to be your minister, and the other a next door neighbour or a doctor or something like that. And I can remember my mother went up
 to Vryce Jamieson, he was the minister. Bryce Jamieson says but I don't know this boy. However - he - he signed - he signed the paper and I got away - before I was age.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 How about temperance clubs, did Greyfriars run any temperance things?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 No. No, the only temperance society was a Recchabites. I don't know whether they're still in being or not. But the - aye. The - th}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16396100\charrsid7372706 e Recchabites was run by - a so}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 licitors - I think it was Hyslop his name, well - well - well you won't know him either - James Hysl
op was the - chief Recchabite in Dumfries.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Did you ever go?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 No. No. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Did you say grace at your meals?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 No. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Did you get taught to say your prayers at night?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Yes. Said your prayers before you went to bed.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Would it be your mother that taught you or one of your big sisters?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 
Oh - I wouldn't like to say who it was that actually taught me. It would probably be my mother. But I can't remember that. But I know we used to say our prayers before we got into bed at night.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Was your father interested in politics at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Not the slightest, he had no interest - other than beyond his Bible, that he showed. Never was out.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 He didn't belong to any clubs?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 No. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Or go to pubs or anything like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 No. He smoked his pipe, but he didn't drink. And - he wasn't a member of any societies or anything like that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 How about your mother?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 She was the same.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Just followed in his footsteps?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Lived her own life, that was her interest in life.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 You say that your parents didn't belong any clubs, what about savings}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16396100\charrsid7372706 -}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 clubs?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Oh - no, you'd no money to save. It took it all.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Nothing like funeral clubs and boot clubs?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Yes. Ah well - ah no, we had nothing like that. We probably h
ad a penny a week life insurance - policies, you know the penny a week - for a - death benefit.. It's about five pound - for a funeral expenses, something like that. But apart from that - we had nothing.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 How did you get on with your brothers and sisters?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Well I was the baby.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 You think you were ruined?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 And - I don't know, I never - seemed to bother much about them at all. I had my jobs outside.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 You weren't friendly with - one of your sisters was quite near you in age wasn't she?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Yes. Oh but we went our own ways. She had her girl friends. And I had boys. Boy pals and we never - you'd never dream of playing with a girl.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 And of course your brothers - there's too big an age difference?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 They were - ah they were away, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 It was your neighbours that you played with then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Was your mother fussy about who you played with or could you play with anybody you fancied?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 I never heard them - never was aware of a - being interested in who I played with. I
 was free to go - and come as I chose. But - it - it - it was all children - round about the doors, that we played together. We never wandered away from home.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 That your mother would have an idea who you were playing with?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Yes, she knew where we were.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 She didn't sort of say don't play with so and so?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 No. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Did you get into trouble if you got dirty when you were playing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 I don't know. I can't remember ever getting - told off. Nor can I remember really - getting dirty. We - w
e would be grubby just the same as other - any other boys and girls but - not - particularly so.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 How about your spare time when you were a schoolboy, did you have any hobbies?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 My spare time - well - when I was a schoolboy round - round about the
 - the age of ten I started to carry milk, for - Taylor of Dalscone, he died here about - many year ago. And I used to get up in the morning - six o'clock every morning, and I got my breakfast and I was at the Mile House, that was a mile out of town, work
i
ng on the milkman coming in at seven o'clock every morning. And - we did our milk deliveries. And - I - I had my school bag with me when I left home at - half past six in the morning. Took my school bag with me. Now - we'd no raincoats, and I don't know w
hat we did when it was a wet morning. Presumably we'd have a - an overcoat on. But - my mother didn't see me home again until - one o'clock. And I was away from - half past six in the morning - to one o'clock. And -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 If it was a wet morning it's a long time to stay wet?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 
And - we had nothing to eat. We had nothing to eat from breakfast time until they come home at dinnertime. And - in the summertime - I used to go to the farm - with the dairyman. I spent all my time then. And I got the princely wag
e of one and tuppence a week. Tuppence a day. Aye. And in the summer time - the milk perhaps came into town at night, there was a milk delivery at night, and you had to do both the morning and the night deliveries for your tuppence a day.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Did they have milk bottles at all in these days?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 No. Cans.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 You measured it out the churns with the measures did you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 What actually happened is - you had the gallon - and a quart and pint cans. And when you set out - to do a milk round - you got certai
n quantity of milk in the - in the large can. And you filled up the smaller cans as it was needed and delivered them houses. Needless to say - if you got a penny at the end of the week when they paid their bill, they always got good measure. The skinflint
s - well they got measure but that was all. Mm hm.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Did you ever collect anything when you were a boy?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 
Cigarette cards? Oh yes, we were collecting cigarette cards. Never collected stamps. Stamps wasn't the vogue, it was cigarette cards in my young days.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Where did you get them, did your father smoke?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 
No. You - you just used to - anybody you saw smoking a cigarette - any cigarette cards mister please? And - once you got one or two, you could always swap, and - if - certain cards were scarc
e, they had a great value, and you had to give one or two or the commoner type to get - a particularly good one, if you wanted a set. Fifty cards now made a set.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 So you were very keen on that?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Oh that was quite a - a job at school. The - playtime it was always cigarette cards. Exchanging.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 How about pets, you would be a bit limited?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Aye, we'd no pets. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Not even a cat?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Well - in later days we - we had both a cat and a dog. But in my early days we had nothing. But we had a 
bulldog and a cat and they were very good pals.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 It's not what you imagine from a bull dog is it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 No. Oh he - it was a she bitch, she was quite a good bulldog.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 How about theatres and you mentioned the shows in the Mechanics Institute and whatnot?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Did you get to go to that sort of thing when you were still at school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 
No. You knew all about them but you never were in the place. We'd no money to pay admission. It was money all the time, but - you - we - never - were greatly concerned to go and see a show.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Did you get any pocket money at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 I got a ha'penny every Saturday. That was my pocket money.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 What did you do with it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Oh it was sweets, yes. You - you got good value those days. I remember - you got
 - a wrapped - square blocks of - different flavour toffee. You got four of those a penny. And it would be what, about two inches square. Four a penny. Two for a happenny. And about hal}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16396100\charrsid7372706 f}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706  a dozen flavours to choose from. And then - there was one or two - toffee shops where we used to go. There was John McNaughts the grocers up in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}St Michaels Street{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}. He made what we called yellow man.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 That's sticky toffee stuff?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Aye, that's long strips of - boiling. And they - he just chopped - them into little pie
ces. Well we got a bagful for a ha'penny. Or you could have - this treacle toffee, it was the same, he just broke it up. And you got a bag for a ha'penny. That was - John McNaughts, and there - there was a shop in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Loreburn Street}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16396100\charrsid7372706 {\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}, Sco}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 ts - the Nethertown da
iry folks. They had a shop - next to the - what was the slaughterhouse and they butter and egg market, and - we used to buy a ha'penny bag of chlorodine rock. That was great value. But it - that was the only - that was the only shop - that you could get -
 chloridine rock. It was - aye, it was -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Chlorodine is stuff you get for a cough is it not?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Aye. Well -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Was that cough candy or something?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 You know - know these - linseed and licorice lozenges, the brown - things. It was the same mate
rial as that it was made of only it was in rolls. Chlorodine rock. And you got a bagful for a ha'penny.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 You never thought of doing anything else with your pocket money?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 No, well - your pocket money - was only the odd ha'penny or penny that someb
ody gave you. Well - you could do nothing - with that - much in the way of toys or anything like that. The main thing was sweets.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 You say your mother didn't take up much with her neighbours?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Mm hm.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Did anybody else help her in the house, just your sisters?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Just the sisters, mm hm.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 What would happen if your mother was ill or anything?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Well that - that's a curious thing, I never - never can remember my mother - ever being ill. But -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 You don't ever remember her being ill in her bed or anything?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 No. If she was ill - then presumably one of my sisters - would have to stay at home to look after the house.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 How about school. Presumably you would go to an ordinary school, you wouldn't get lessons from parents or tutors or anything like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 No, no. We went to Laurieknowe school, that was my first school.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Did you start at five?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Did you go all day when you started, or did you go for a half day for the first year or so?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 I - I couldn't real
ly tell you, I don't remember. No, I couldn't - I couldn't really say - how long we went. But I know we used to be scared stiff - there was an attendance officer round {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Dumfries{\*\xmlclose}
 that time. They Cancel, you may have heard of the family? He was an ex-Ar}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16396100\charrsid7372706 m}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 y Ser
geant Major, and he got the job as an Attendance officer. He used to cycle about the town. If he ever saw a child who should - who he thought should have been at school and wasn't, he'd jump off the bike and he'd come over to the - kid, and - cross examin
e the kid as to why he was not at school, what school he'd go to. Although it was none of his business, he was the only the education attendance officer for certain schools. He poked his nose - into - everybody's - business.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Did you ever play truant?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 No. No, I - I got on well at school. Aye.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 You say you went to Laurieknowe?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Laurieknowe school.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 That was just an ordinary public school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 And then where did you go on to?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Oreburn Street{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
 school, when we went - flitted out to - to the other road.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 When you were about nine?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Aye. We went - I went to {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Loreburn Street{\*\xmlclose}
{\*\xmlclose} school. And - it only took pupils up to the sixth standard. And - then beyond that, they had - classes in those days which were known as supplementa
ry. Supplementary, one, two, three - four. That took you on until you were fourteen. The sixth standard took you on to - I suppose it'd be the equivalent of the qualifying standard.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 About eleven or twelve?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Mm hm. And then you went to {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}George Street{\*\xmlclose}
{\*\xmlclose}. That was the final - stage. It wasn't a high school. It was - it - it - it - took all children, of various ages right up - but they had the supplementary classes there.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Why would you go to Laurieknowe school? It would take you quite a while to walk from the house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Well - our house - when I was born was Observatory Terrace, down \{BLANK\}
 Street, and of course, the natural school was Laurieknowe, the natural town school.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Even though you had shifted after that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 And - well we just carried on.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Was it a case of your brothers and sisters all went to Laurieknowe and you followed?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 That was the family school, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 It's not like nowadays if you live in a certain district -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 You must go to a certain school, no, no, you coul
d - I think I'm right in saying if you lived anywhere in Marshaltown you had to go to a Marshaltown school. But if again if you lived in Dumfries - well I - I didn't go to a {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Dumfries{\*\xmlclose}
 school, I went to Laurieknowe. And then my brothers and sisters, they were at Laurieknowe too, so there couldn't have been any - hard and fast rules that I knew - from going to a school outside your own - area.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Did you manage to get home for your dinner?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Yes. Mm hm.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 How long did it take you to walk?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Oh we didn't walk we run. Ten minutes, aye, ten}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16396100\charrsid7372706  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 minutes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Did you go with your brothers and sisters to school or were you independent?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Independent. We just set out - we - we - we probably go - set off together, but if we - met other children on the way
 then we probably - would leave the - our brothers or sisters, and - go off with our pals.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Your pals from round about the door wouldn't be going to the same school would they?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 No. But - on the way to the school, the way - the road that we went.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 
The way we went school, we went over the suspension bridge, and along the Mill Green, do you know where the Mill Green is - that's right, past the Green Mills, they were - which were operating in those days, the town grain mills, and - through onto 
Market Square, and - onto Galloway Street. And up {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Galloway Street{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} the boys entrance was at the top of Laurieknowe.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 It must have been a temptation for boys dithering on their way to school going along the side of the river was it not?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 No. No, I d
on't - but we never had time. Like - you run all the way home at dinnertime. You wouldn't run back, you'd run home but you'd - walk back, and you always - well you picked up school pals on the way. School children live - living on the - on the route you w
aited for one another and - went back to school with them.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 What did you think about school in general, did you enjoy it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Yes, I think I enjoyed it. I think I can safely say that, because - I don't mean anything when I say it but I seemed to be ab
le to do all the - subjects that were taught without any great difficulty.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 How did you feel about the teachers?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 I got on well with the teachers, many of the pennies I got - for carrying the books home for the teachers. At four o'clock - I - ther
e was a Miss Holmes, she lived down {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Queen Street{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
. I - perhaps she used to come and say, would you take those books home, exercise books for marking, and I got a penny for taking them, and bringing them back next morning, That was - penny was a lot, mm hm. 
Oh she was very good to me with the pennies, I got a lot of pennies from her.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 How about the headmasters?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Headmasters, well - Arnott was the headmaster at Laurieknowe when I was there. And - I don't remember much about it, apart from the fact - h
e was a widower, and he married one of the girls at school.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 That would be a scandal I bed?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Well -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 She would be very much younger?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Oh yes. I can remember that, it was talked about at the time. D.R. Arnott. He had his family at school 
and - this girl was in the supplementary class, and he got in tow with her and ultimately married her.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Did the teachers emphasise certain things as being important, like good manners or being tidy or punctual, this sort of thing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 If you were lat
e you got a walloping. So - that was - punctuality. You - got a walloping you got - the strap if you were late and hadn't a - a good excuse.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Did you get it from the teachers?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Yes. Yes. Mm hm.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 How about being tidy?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Tidy, well - I don't
 know. When I - I went to school at first we had no books or pencils, it was slates and slate pencils, and - you had a wet rag in your pocket for cleaning down the slate. So that you'd know - you'd no - writing material.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 No books to keep tidy?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 N
o. And you - your other books of course, they were supplied by the school. And - handed out and taken back in but - never had any difficulty - we - we didn't abuse our books in any way.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Did the teachers teach you to speak in any particular way?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 None of the children got told off for being broad spoken or anything like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Oh well you didn't - didn't - talk in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Dumfries{\*\xmlclose} - English.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 You had two ways of talking?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Oh yes. Oh yes, aye. Aye. No, you - you - you'd talk more or le
ss proper in the classroom. You - you didn't when you got out, you had your own {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Dumfries{\*\xmlclose} - language.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 What about at home then? Did you talk school English at home?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Oh no, just - everyday - everyday Scots. Mm hm.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Did - the teachers use that strap a lot?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Oh yes, I think he strap was fairly well - used. You'd see it in use three or four times a day.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 For what sort of things?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Carelessness in your lessons.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Not for stupidity?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Not paying attention. And carelessness. Stupi
dity wasn't recognised I don't think. We were all supposed to be equal, we were all being taught alike and you were supposed to - assimilate what you were taught. So - there was no - I don't think - you could say that they recognised stupidity - in school
.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Was there any difference made between the girls and the boys as far as getting the belt was concerned?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Don't think so, no. There were more boys got the belt than girls, but that was only natural because - the lads were always up to some sort of
 mischief or other and - were getting pulled out for it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 It hasn't changed has it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Were your parents interested in what you were doing at school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Don't think so.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 You weren't cross examined when you went home about what you'd been doing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 No. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Would your parents visit the school at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 No. No, there was no visiting. No parents visited the schools in my young days. No, you just accepted everything as it came.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Your mother wouldn't know the teachers?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 If we pointed out the teacher. That's Miss so and so. But there was no contact with the school.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 How about the other children in your class, did they all come from homes similar to yours or were there some better off and some worse off?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 I don't
 know, I think we were all more or less of a standard. There was no - nobody - none of the idle rich or anything like that. The idle rich went to the Academy. Which was a fee paying school there. But - the rest of us at the board schools as we called them
, we were more or less - all the same class.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 
Did you find that the teachers singled out any of the children for special treatment, you know, either to be extra nice to them or to be extra hard on them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Well - I don't know, you often - have - they
 could say, oh she's a teachers favourite, but I don't think there was anything really in it. The teacher was bound to have - it's only natural, that she would be better pleased with clever pupils than what she would with say stupid ones. But - it never s
howed itself to my knowledge in any way, there was no favouritism.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Not even getting a penny for talking the books home?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Oh well that wasnae favouritism.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 You had to earn it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Mm hm. But you never got any - prizes or presents from the teacher for good work. Like she never gave you a}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid16396100\charrsid7372706  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 
penny or - if you'd done - good work. You never got any recognition. I suppose teachers would be poorly paid and just - money meant as much to them as it did to us.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Did they have prizes for work at say the end of the session?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Yes. Yes. You got prizes. Have you see these - school prize books? Well -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Did you find there were any gangs or special groups in the school while you were there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 The only - gang, you couldn't call them gangs, was - at St Patrick}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16396100\charrsid7372706 \rquote }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 
s Day. We - the Catholic children and the Protestant children met on Devorgilla's Bridge, and we had paper balls tied with string, and we swung these round our head, and when you met another kid, what's hour colour? Green for Catholic, blue for 
Protestant. And if it was the wrong colour they got walloped with a ball. Or you got walloped with the ball, but - St Patricks Day there was always - it wasn't a stand up fight, but there was a battle with the paper balls, on Deborgilla's Bridge.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 But you would be quite pally with the Catholics the next day?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 
Well - not - we didn't mix. Catholics and Protestants, not to my - not in my memory. We were - roundabout me we were all Protestants, I wouldn't say - there wasn't a great deal of Catholics - in the town in those days.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 And they would go to their own school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}St Andrews{\*\xmlclose}
 school, yes. But - there wasn't a great number - they were greatly in the minority. In town.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 How were they treated in general, the Catholics, were they looked down on or were they just treated like ordinary people?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 
Well - I don't know but you - you - you had the impression that everybody looked down their - snitch at them. Their nose at them. They're just P}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16396100\charrsid7372706 o}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 pes, or Catholics. That was it. You'd no time for them.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 You weren't friendly with any of them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Did you find it much different when you went to Loreburn after Laurieknowe?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Mm, now.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 You would be leaving all your friends behind?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Ah well I can't remember much about it now, but I suppose I - I had to leave and that was the end of it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 That was generally an upset in your life at that time anyway?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Well I suppose - yes, changing school like that, but - not - I don't remember - how it affected me.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 You left school at fourteen?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Fourteen.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 If you'd had the chance would you have liked to stay on?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 I could have got the chance. The headmaster at {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}
Loreburn Street{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} did his utmost to push me to the Academy. You got in - free then, with a bursary.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 The bright boys from {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}George Street{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
 would get the chance of free education?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Yes. It's before that - no, before you went to George Street. At Loreburn Street.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 At twelve or so?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Yes. The bright boys sat the bursary examinations. And - if they were succe
ssful they got - to the Academy. And I remember Waddell, he was the headmaster - he pestered me for days - to - get me to sit the bursary examination. And I said no. And they said well what is your reason why you don't want to sit it? I said, because my m
other requires me to go out working to bring in a wage.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 What did your mother say about it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Well -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Was she really keen on you going out to work?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 No, mother - mother was hard up. It was after my father died. There was no pensions or anyt
hing like that. And - the natural things was - well - I was fourteen, had been looked after 'til I was fourteen, and I had the feeling, right, well I'm going out now to get a wage, and I'm not going further with education.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 All your mother would have coming in would be what your sister brought in?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Shillings a week, mm hm.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 It can't have been very easy for her?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 No it wasn't. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Have you ever regretted not staying on longer?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 No. I don't know - that I - actually missed anything, because I went to a firm of law agents, Symons MacDonald. In 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Irish Street{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
, and - John Symons was a treasurer to the Dumfries Infirmary, and in 1915 - when the military service act came into - force, Symons and MacDonald lost all their young men. With the 
result that I was only in my second year apprenticeship, and I was stepped up in the job, I became John Symons's - boy at the meetings. And I used to go to all these infirmary meetings every week, and I wrote the minutes of these meetings at fifteen.

\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 The sort of job that you probably wouldn't have normally done until you were in your twenties?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Until the time was right, aye. Five years apprenticeship, aye, twenty.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Did they send you to night school or anything like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 No, they didn't, but I went myself. Shorthand and typewriting I went for.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Not book keeping,
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 No. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Where did you go for that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 To the Academy. Academy evening classes. I think the book keeping in it, when you say it. But I know it was - the shorthand I was after.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 For taking minutes and so on?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 
Mm hm. Well - I got a good grounding there, that I wouldn't have got if I'd gone to the Academy. Like - it fitted me out for later years in - in life. So that - don't - I don't think I lost a great de
al in not going to the Academy. I may have lost a - I may have got a better job but - it went all right in the end.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Generally you're quite happy about your education?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Yes. Mm hm. Mm hm. I made my own way when I left school.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Can you tell me about your part time jobs? You said that you delivered milk?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 I was a milk boy. Mm hm. One and tuppence a week.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 How come you got a job like that, did you go and ask for it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 No, you just went to the milkman.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Were some of your pals doing the same sort of job?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 
Oh well, each milkman had about half a dozen boys. And they all carried milk. If one left - then there was a vacancy there for somebody - a younger boy.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 How old would you be when you started doing that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Well this - eleven or twelve.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Then you had your lemonade and your bread you weren't paid for?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Oh I wasn't paid, no, no, that was just - companionship.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Did you do any other wee jobs like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 You stuck to the milk delivery?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 The mil
k and in the summertime - I went to the farm. But I got nothing extra for it. I worked there at the farm, a labourer, I worked for the men, and all that I got with my - midday meal and my tea at night before I come away with the milk cart.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 You didn't get anything at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Didn't get a penny piece.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 You would just get the same pay as you got for delivering?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 One and tuppence a week.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 They were on a good thing there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Oh well - quite a lot of the boys went out there - to the farm. 
It was good fun. We used to - we got a horse to drive and all that sort of thing you see
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 And helping with hay making and this sort of thing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Yes. The harvesting, summertime, this - the summer holidays.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Did you do any milking?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Oh no. No, no. That was beyond me, no, that was a woman's job. Milking.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 How about your milk deliveries on Sundays?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Aye. We went out on a Sunday morning - just the same.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 What did your parents have to say about that?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Ah well, it was later you see, that was 1910 or 1911 - my father was dead.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Do you think he would have approved of you going out doing work on a Sunday?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 No. Well he went out on the Sunday. He went out - out on a Sunday - late on the Sunday afternoon to prepare for the Mon
day morning's - bakery. I think that they had preparative work to do the day before. And I think - from memory he went out about three or four o'clock on the Sunday.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 So it was all right doing work on Sundays so long as you didn't play?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Well there was no - no playing on Sunday, you - you didn't get out to play, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 You said the magazines and papers were put under the cushions?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 They were all put away, aye, you weren't allowed to - to look at anything.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 What did you do with your one and tuppence a week?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Gave it to my mother.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 You handed it all over?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Mm hm. Mm hm.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 How did you get on with your employer and the people that you were working with?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 We got on very very will them, mm hm.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Did you enjoy farm work?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Aye, I was quite happy.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Not sufficient to make you think about doing it full time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 
I never - oh I wouldn't have taken - never dreamt of taking it up. The - the the farm labourer's pay then was half a crown a day. And - the - the farm labo
urer, I remember this fellow he - he lived at the foot of the High Street, and he started seven o'clock in the morning. And he got a midday meal. And they got an afternoon - jug of tea. And they finished at six o'clock. And half a crown was his pay for th
e day's work. From seven o'clock in the morning to six o'clock at night. Half a crown. That was twelve and six a week, didn't work on a Sunday. And they had - oh a - a great -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16396100\charrsid7372706 Di}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 d they get free milk and potatoes and things like that?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 No. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 They get that sort of thing nowadays.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 
Aye. No, no, you got no perks. You got a - a jug of milk with your dinner provided there was sufficient left over after the - carts had come back from town. The milk carts. He had two milk - two other - two mil
k carts. And - used to have the left over milk.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 But you never had the feeling that you wanted to leave school and go on the farm?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Oh no, I never took any notion, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 How about your full time job, Symons and MacDonald, how did you get it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 
MacDonald - went to - George Street school and saw the headmaster, told him - he was looking for a boy, and - Waddell came to me and said he'd got - this offer of a good job, what about it? I went home and told mother and she said, well - if you want i
t go for it, so - I went along and saw MacDonald and I got the job. I can remember fine, he said, there's only one thing that will be wrong. One difficulty. They sat on these high stools in those days. With - a sloped desk. He said, how are you going to m
anage up on the stool? I don't know, I was - small for my age, mm hm. But he said - everything else was OK. So I went there. I got ten pounds a year. I don't know whether I told you this before.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 And you were paid quarterly?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Paid quarterly and put
 a tuppenny stamp on the receipt before we got it, it was over two pound. So that was thirteen weeks you'd to work before you got your two pound ten.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 In a way your mother would be worse off for the first three months then because she wouldn't have your milk round money coming in?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 She had nothing. That's right, she had nothing.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 And you would need new clothes and so on for your job?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Aye, well we wore our Sunday clothes. Didn't have a new - new rigout, aye. And I remember I wore the starc
hed white collar - when I first went to Symons and Macdonald.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Were they very fussy about what you wore to an office like that?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 No. I never heard any - them express anything. They were all quietly dressed. They all wore suits and they all - all 
wore the suits and - the - the typists - they were just ordinarily - dressed you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 How many were in the office, was it quite a big office?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Oh it was a big office, probably be about twenty of us staff.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 That's quite big.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Mm hm.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Of course an awful it had to be done by hand in those days?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 
It was all done by - it was all done by hand except the - the typists, they had - three typists. There shorthand typists. All the business ledgers, they were all hand written of course.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Was that the sort of job that you got to do to start with?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 No. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 How did you start off?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 I was a - office boy. You run messages.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 And making the tea?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 No. There was no tea. Oh no, no. I - you didn't get any tea in those days. N
o, any of the - clerks that wanted - any - messages or papers looked out, they just rung the bell and you went forward and they told you what they wanted and away you went - do the - do the searching for just what they wanted. Run them messages. And the o
ld fellow - the senior clerk, he used to take a hold of all the young - youthful boys that came into the firm, and he put them through a course of - handwriting.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Was he not satisfied with what you learned at school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 No, you'd to learn to do the l
egal handwriting. You've seen that legal copyright handwriting. Well - you'd got to learn to do that so that when you're writing deeds - that you could - write them as they were supposed to be written.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Was it much different from what you'd been taught at school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Oh yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 I thought you were taught copyright at school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 
No it was all plain writing. But the legal - writing was entirely different. And he used to come round and - get your pen, toss it to the other side of the room. Who you t
old you to write like that? And you got a lecture from him, because you'd made a mistake in the writing.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Of course you wouldn't be allowed to make mistakes in deeds and things?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Oh no, of course we weren't writing deeds, we were only practicing on the paper. But - he was a holy terror.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 What was the next stage after being the office boy?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 
Then - I stepped up to the - treasurers - mess - message boy I think you could - well - assistant - I did everything that he required to do, other than 
present himself at the meetings. Like we had a meeting every Tuesday, and - both of us went down there and - I had all the paraphe}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16396100\charrsid7372706 rnali}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 a with me of course and - made the notes and - when I went back to the office - prepared the minutes and submitted the dr
aft to the boss and he amended it as he saw fit. We got all the correspondence done, and - that was infirmary and then the district committee - that was a county council office. Symons again was clerk to the district committee, and of course it was again 
- a case of going to the meetings, preparing minutes and - doing the job. But it was amazing how the - you feel into it. Never presented any difficulty to me.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 But Mr Symons kept an eye on things himself?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Oh well he was responsible. And everything
 you wrote - went through him. He - he approved of it before you - got it typed or that sort of - but it was a good training. It - it was a good training. I thought. You know, learn something at the end of the day.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 How far had you advanced then when you came to join up?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Ah well I went away when I was seventeen and a half, I volunteered to join up in the forces. And - I was doing these jobs - until I left.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 As you say, having more responsibility than you would have if the seniors hadn't gone off to war?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 I would never have had the opportunity of the seniors hadn't gone off to the war.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 What made you decide to sign on?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 To get into the Flying Corps. You'd to go before you were eighteen.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Why was this?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 If you waited until
 you were eighteen you were called up under Conscription Act. But if you went away before you were eighteen you could - make your own choice where you wanted to go. And I wanted to go into the Flying Corps.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Why, was it the glamour service even in those days?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Oh no, it - it was only - I mean - it was only in in its infancy. Oh flying.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Had you done any?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Oh no. No, I'd never - never seen an aeroplane. Well - there must have been very few, I - I can remember the first - aeroplane that flew
 over the country - Heriot - and Bleriot. The Frenchman. There would probably be about two hundred folks - at five o'clock in the morning, went - walked up to the Craigs, you know where the Craigs is? They walked up there at five o'clock in the morning, t
o await on Bleriot passing overhead, and his plane, and the beggar went up by Locherby. So we - we never saw him, and there was the two hundred souls - on a summers morning.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 You too?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Oh yes, I was there.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 That was as near as you got to an aeroplane before you joined up?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 
Well that was the first aeroplane. That would be 1909. Oh no, probably - I don't know - aye, was it - those flying circuses - would that be after the war. That was after the war, the flying circuses. No, I don't think we 
would get the opportunity of seeing - much of things.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 So you signed on, can you tell me what happened to you then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Well - I went down to {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Hastings{\*\xmlclose}, on the {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}
English Channel{\*\xmlclose} - and - that was - my training there finished about - March 1918. That was 
the infantry training. No. That was the infantry training. And then - there was a - a ruling came down - that no further cadets had to be - technically trained. They didn't want any more, they had sufficient. Whether or not they knew that the end of the w
ar - was in sight. And the time it took to technically train - a man - they probably thought, well - we've got sufficient - pilots in the pipe line. And -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 That would be coming up for 1918?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Oh well that was March 18. Aye}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16396100\charrsid7372706 . So - back we went to our infa}{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 ntry regiments.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 I think you said you were sent to {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Hamilton{\*\xmlclose}
{\*\xmlclose}?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 No, I went - I went to Wormit, up by {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Dundee{\*\xmlclose}. From {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Hastings{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}. And then - later - after the Armistice - I was - pushed down to {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Hamilton{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
 as a clerk in the - at the office there. And I was there for about a year. And again I got on very well there, and they wanted me to go down to {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}London{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
 - on an accountancy course under which you could qualify as a chartered accountant. And they - stood all the expenses and all the rest of it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Were you not tempted by that then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 
No. I said, no, I'm going home. I'm going home, so - I finally went - got back home and went - to see my old employers, Symons and MacDonald - they offered me forty pounds a year salary, paid quarterly. I said, no, I cou
ld never live on that. It's useless to think of it. So then - I got a job as a progress clerk out at Arol Johnsons, that was motor car industry.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Did that pay a bit better then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 They were paying you every week?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Oh yes, paid weekly
. And I was there for a - a while and until - there was a slackness came into the motor industry and of course - well of course that - aye. Aye, we were pushed out, and - a fellow from the inland Revenue -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 You were saying that the man from the Inland Revenue came?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 
Came along to the door one day at dinnertime, and - he said, I believe - you have clerical experience and I was looking for a job. Did the Inland Revenue appeal to me? I said, oh I'll try anything once. So I got fixed up in the Inland R
evenue. And - that was the start of my career.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Did you get paid quite well in those days?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 
Oh yes. I - I can't tell you know. It was a - an age - a wage for age. You were paid according to your - age, and I remember I used to feel very sorry - so
re about it. There was an elderly lady there, she was a clerkess, and - she was as wooden as - any door, and she was getting about three times the wage that I was getting. I was under twenty-one at the time, and I could only get the wage - for a - a clerk
 of twenty. Twenty years of age. However we got over it all and I progressed. Quite happy.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 I supposed with the Revenue you would have security?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Which was quite something at that time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Oh well, no, I don't think we were really int
erested in security, it was a job. It was a job, and - the longer you were on the job the more interested - that you got in the job. And it had quite a good career then. In fact my son's followed on. Aye, he's in the Inland Revenue now, he's - principle i
nspector of taxes up in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Glasgow{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}. And he's the youngest - when he got his promotion he was the youngest ever - to get to that - that grade.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 So you were quite happy in the career that you chose for yourself?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Oh yes, I couldna have done better.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Did you ever belong to any professional organisation?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 None whatever. None whatever, I'd no time for it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Did you feel that your employers and workers had the same interests or different interests?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Aye, there was no - no questions of the em
ployers just - you had your instructions what was to be done, you trained your staff to do the job and that was the end of it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Would you say that working full time changed your general attitude to life in any way?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 No, you just accepted it it was progress.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 You were just growing up?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Yes. And - it - it wasn't a longer working day. When I started out in Symons and MacDonald}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid16396100\charrsid7372706 \rquote s}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 , we started at nine o'clock in the morning. And we got an hour off for our lunch. And then the office boys, there was three of us, we got three}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16396100\charrsid7372706  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 
quarters of an hour off for tea, between four and five o'clock. And we were going back at five o'clock - and we'd to wait until the bosses had signed all the correspondence, and made it ready for despatch before we could quit t
he office. And it was mostly seven o'clock at nights before we got away.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 So it was quite a long day?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 It was a long day.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 How did you get on with your boss, with Mr Symons?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Very well.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Was he the sort of person who looked on his workers as part of the family?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 No. No, no, as long as the job went all right, that was all he was interested in.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 And if it went wrong what was he like?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Well I never had experience of anything going wrong. No. But - aye, the relationship you know was very good with them, with both partners.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 One difference after you started working, you might have had a different life after work?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Well, I suppose - we did.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Would you still be staying at home?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 I was still at home. And it was only a question you started to go out at night with your pals.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Did your mother have any rules and regulations about that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 None whatever. You were free to go and come as you - pleased.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Was there something that just happened once you started working?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 
Once I started working, yes. We started going out at night because we had it to spend then. Well, when I say money - a couple of bob in the pocket or something like that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 How did you work your finances then, say when you started working?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 I got a shilling a week from my mother for pocket money.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 And the rest would go towards your keep?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 The two pound ten went to her at the end of the quarter.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 So that's about half each you would get?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Thirteen - well I had thirteen shillings - pocket money.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Did she still buy your clothes then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Oh yes. Uh huh.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 So you could spend your shilling on what you wanted?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 I could do what I liked with my bob.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 You say you stopped going to church then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 I stopped, aye, before that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Were you interested in politics at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Never.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Followed in father's footsteps?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 No interest in politics.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Can you tell me what you did do in your spare time then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Well - at nights, we had - in the summertim
e we used to go rowing a boat up the Nith. I remember that, I - every night of the week it was fine. If it was wet we'd play billiards.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 I presume you hired the boat?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Oh yes. The rowing club, the - the - the - they had a rowing club but we weren'
t members of the rowing club, we just hired the boat. Went for a couple of hours.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 That's in an ordinary rowing boat?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 An ordinary rowing boat and went up the - Nith. As far as - Cludon, then back down. And that was more or less your evening put in.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 And if it was wet you played billiards?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Played billiards.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 I gather you went with boys then?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Oh yes. Aye. Oh there was no girls. No girls. No time for girls.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 We were talking about the billiards rooms the other day?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Uh huh.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16396100\charrsid7372706 Were there}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706  places where you drank as well as play billiards?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 No. You could get a - a mineral to drink. But there was no liquor.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Nothing stronger?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 No, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 So your mother would be quite happy about you going out to do that sort of thing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Oh I don't think she ever gave it a thought.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 How about girls then, how long was it before you started to take an interest in them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 I would say in about 1917, at the evening classes. Where we met the girls. We began to get friendly then.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Girls going to the same classes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Yes. But - never had a girl for any length of time like - go with a girl for maybe - a month or so and then change over to somebody else.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Would you tend to go out with just one girl or did you go out in a crowd of you all together?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 No, just ourselves. Just ourselves.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 You just picked one out?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Mm hm.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 For a short term?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 In fact - it really was escorting a girl home from the night school, that was most it, two nights or three ni
ghts a week. The weekends we - we were with our pals. That was -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Did you ever get round to taking girls home at that stage?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 A}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16396100\charrsid7372706 h}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 
 well from - coming from the night classes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 But taking them to your home?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Oh no. No. That would be as much as your life was worth. No, no, you'd no money - to entertain - a girl in any way.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Was your mother interested to know what you were doing then and who you were doing it with?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 No. I don't think she ever worried herself. No. Oh she knew that it was only boy and girl friendship. There was nothing - in it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 
Do you think there would be any difference in the way she treated and the way she treated your sisters as far as that's concerned? Would she want to know who they were going out with?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Don't think so, because they used to go to the dances and they had their by friends. But they never came to the house.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Not at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Did you go to dances?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 After - after I came back from the army. I went to dances - I learned dancing - when I was up in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Hamilton{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
 in the Duke of Hamilton's grounds. One hut was - we - they used to have surprise parties, the girls in the pay office would come along to them, and they'd say, be at the Cross at seven o'clock tonight, we're going to so and so's 
house. Now so and so didn't know that we were coming. But the girls provided all the eats. And we went along and took possession of that house - for the evening. We had a grand time.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 How many of you would there be?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 There might be - couple of dozen. Mm hm. That was in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Hamilton
{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}. And I learned to dance one nights, there was a fellow, Wattie Houston, he was a - he - he was - coming out to be a doctor, I expect he would be - but he was a fiddler. So - he said to me - this night in 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceName}}Hamilton{\*\xmlclose} {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceType}}Palace{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} grou
nds when we were passing boy, he said, come on we'll have a dance and we'll see what you can do with it. So he started to fiddle, and the others - started to learn me how to dance. So from there I went to dancing classes. Oh and I had a grand time up at H
amilton.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 What kind of dancing was it you learned?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 All the figure dances.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 The Lancers and Quadrilles?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Yes. Mm hm.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Were you too young to go to dances when you lived in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Dumfries{\*\xmlclose}, before you joined up?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Never had - anything to do with girls was taboo, you'd no time for girls.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Even at seventeen?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 
Mm hm. No, no time for girls. And I think the trace - the - the trait passed onto my son because I can remember him being at a - a school party at Paisley Grammar school - at th
e end of term, and when he come home we asked him how he enjoyed it. I enjoyed it fine if there had been no girls there.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 A woman hater?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 He wasn't a woman hater but - then again - he couldn't be doing with the girls.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Are there any other ways that you entertained yourself in those days? What about pictures by then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 There was no pictures. No pictures, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Or shows?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 The - the first pictures that I can remember - oh they'd be pictures, I was a boy. I was still at school and we us
ed to go to the electric theatre in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Shakespeare Street{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
 on the Saturday morning. And - you got the Pearl White thrillers, serial, a penny a Saturday. But that was only time - we never were in for pictures during the week. Saturday mornings we spent - a penny.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Even when you were working?; Didn't you go to pictures at night?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Don't think so because we didn't have money.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 A shilling didn't take you all that far?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 We hadn't the money. And I don't think there was any - the Electric Theatre was 
the first picture house. When the Lyceum - come into operation I wouldn't care to say. But - I can remember going to the Electric Theatre on a Saturday morning for the penny thriller. And - the Pearl White thrillers - It was always a serial. Mm hm.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 What about outings? In those days.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 We never had a holiday. I never had a holiday until after I come back from the army.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 What about out for the day?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 No. No. No, what - what we used to do on a Saturday afternoon, we'd go for - Glencapel, we u
sed to walk - on a Saturday afternoons right round Gelncapel. Caerlaverock back and back home. That was a Saturday afternoon's walk.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 It's quite a long walk?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Well that - that was - if it was a decent afternoon. That was the walk.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 That was just with your friends?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Mm hm.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 You wouldn't think of having a family walk?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 We never went with the family, no, no. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Did your mother go out much at that time then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 No. No, but it was more of the time we lived at {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Nith Place
{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}, that there was a customary walk on the Sunday afternoon. Apart from going - up town to do her shopping that would be about the only time she was out.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 If after your father died she had gone out a bit more than she did before?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 No, I would think it was 
the other way about. Didn't go out, well - she only did her messages before. And she would still do that, so it would be no - no great change you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 No great visiting?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 No visiting, no, we never went - visiting any houses.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 What about your friends when you were working, did you ever go to your friends houses then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 
Well - I - used to run - with a fellow, Charlie Frazer, he's dead now, he was a sanitary surveyor, and occasionally I've seen me go into his house, but he never was in my ho
use. I used to go and pick him up there. But - never - I never had a meal in his house, never was entertained or anything like that,. Go along to see if he was ready to come out and you're invited into the house for a minute or two until he was ready. But
 - there was no - visiting - between houses.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 
Talking about eating, when you were out say for a walk or out at night after you'd maybe been on the river, would you go and eat something on the way home?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 No. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Were there chip shops in those days?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 
Yes, there were chip shops. In - in my - article there in the Standard I refer to a Mr Duckett. Who was a fish and chip proprietor and a prominent member of the Salvation Army, well - I had a funny sort of - thought at the time, and I hurried d
own - he saved souls on the Sunday, and he battered them all the remainder of the week. But that's not - that's not - that's not fair. Fish and chip fryer.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 But you wouldn't go to a chip shop?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 No, didn't dislike the smell of - vinegar. Therefore I had no time for fish and chips.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Did your mother expect you to be home by a certain time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 There was no time limit?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 We were free to go and come. No rules.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 What about mealtimes though?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Oh well you knew - you knew when the meals were being served and you had to be there. Mm hm.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Otherwise you did without?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Well, you defeated yourself.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 So you would be there in time rather than see to yourself?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Aye. Mm hm.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 At the beginning of this session Mr Small 
recalled he had been thinking about his mother's washing and where she had dried it, and when the weather was good there was a public washer drying green on Dock Park which would be maybe one to two hundred yards away from his home with lots of clothes po
l
es there and the ladies of the neighbourhood took their washing down there and dried it on the public drying green. Mr Small thinks that his mother would only use this when the weather was really good as the drying green was out of sight of the house and 
she didn't want to leave her washing there any longer than she had to. And also she didn't want it to be caught in a shower of rain when she would have to run all that way to collect the washing before it got wet again.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 You said -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 It occurred to 
me after you went away that - we used to have to take the washing along to Miss Dunbar's - house in the - in the evening, and we paid a penny, and we mangled the clothes. She had the mangle.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Your mother didn't have a mangle of her own?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 No. No. N
o mangle. And we got all the clothes mangled. You mangled them yourself. And you paid the lady a penny for the use of her mangle. Oh she had quite a clientele.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Was it one of these gre}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16396100\charrsid7372706 a}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 t big mangles?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Yes, the old fashioned one, aye. Metal frame.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 You did the work yourself?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 You had to work it yes. She - she charged a penny for the use of the mangle.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 That would be quite an investment I suppose?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Well I suppose she'd - she'd have ten or twelve - customers a week. And a penny was a penny.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 It would all help?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Aye. Well, we took the basket up with the washing, mangled it and brought it back. So that was another - method of getting rid of the wash.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Remember you saying your father had a violin that he played a lot?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Were there any other musical instruments in the house?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 He had}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16396100\charrsid7372706  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 none. No.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 You didn't have a piano in the parlour?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 No. No, no, nothing at all.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Did you any of you children learn the violin?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 None at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 No.
 My brother used to play the tin whistle. He had a tin whistle, and I used to have the - well of course - that was long after their days. I had an accordi}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16396100\charrsid7372706 o}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 n. I played the accordi}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16396100\charrsid7372706 o}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 n. So that there was a musical touch - was there behind it all. But we'd no -
 no instruments apart from his violin.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 It seems strange that he didn't encourage any of you to follow in his footsteps?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 I don't suppose he'd ever think.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 How old would you be when you started the accordi}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16396100\charrsid7372706 o}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 n then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 I - about twelve.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Did you go out for lessons?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 
No, no. No, just - picked it up myself. Then later on - I - only - when we - began to - I had got a - I got a portable - record player, a Decca. I - I suppose it would be ancient compared with the present - record players,
 but I used to play records often up in my own room just the same as my father used to do, after tea at night and I used to - used the accordi}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16396100\charrsid7372706 o}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 n to the accompaniment of the record - that's where I learned a lot of the tunes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 You didn't sort of have musical evenings all together?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang1034\langfe1033\langnp1034\insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang1034\langfe1033\langnp1034\insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Never - no, no, no, no. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 No, as I say, the evenings - after the tea was cleared, well it would be about eight o'clock. And then the sewing, the girls had their sewing, and - by the time you got down there and had a chinwag it was suppertime, bedtime.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 You didn't sort of sing together when the girls were working?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 No. No. Never the girls - were musically inclined.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 How about your mother, was she a singer or not?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 No. No. No, I think it came from my father's side. Mm hm.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 And the boys inherited it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Well - my brother and myself. These are the only two I know that - took up - music in the way.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 You say you just had a chinwag at night, did you ever play any games in the house? That your mother mig
ht have joined in with you, like card games or dominies?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 No, cards - cards were taboo.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Altogether?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Oh yes, no cards. I - there was an old games that we - we - had many a happy hour with. Blanchet, have you ever heard of it? Now - it was a 
piece of wood shaped like a heart. And it had three legs, one at each corner, with a little wheel on the end of each leg. And it was only certain individuals - that could operate it. But - you put blanchet on the table on a - sheet of white paper, and you
 
all got a chance of asking - blanchet a question. And - my sister - one of my sister's, Hetty, she was the only one that could operate this blanchet. And ask a question she didn't know the answer, but she just put - put her hands on blanchet and it starte
d to write. And it gave you an answer to the question.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Were the answers right?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 
Well - it was amazing the fun we got out of it. I remember one Sunday afternoon, how this should stick I - I don't know, but - mother wasn't in the room and blanchet w
as brought out, it's after - after my father dead, blanchet was brought out and - somebody, one of my sisters - said - come on }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16396100\charrsid7372706 b}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 
lanchet, what's mother doing? And the answer written on paper was - something she shouldn't be doing. And when we went upstairs to see what she was doing she was cutting buttons off old clothes. On a Sunday afternoon. Isn't it amazing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Your mother didn't approve of cards but she was quite happy to let you do that sort of thing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Oh yes, she didn't know it was being done o
f course. Well she was away up - upstairs at amongst the old clothes. Aye. But I always remember that answer, something she shouldn't be doing. But oh we'd lots of fun with }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16396100\charrsid7372706 b}{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 lanchet.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 How about books in your house, apart from the prize ones that you won at school were there many books?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 I don't think there'd be any books except those that were won as prizes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Was there a library in those days?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Did you go to the library?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Didn't go to the library, no, but the Ewart was there. I wasn't a reader as a kid - as a kid.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 How about comics and things?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Yes, we used to buy the comics. The Gem and the Magnet.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Did you have to buy them with your own pocket money?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Oh yes. No. Aye. What you did was you - you bought one
 and you swapped it - with some of the other boys for another one, and you probably - got a read of half a dozen of these boys magazines for the price of one. That's how it was done.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 How about papers and things, did you have a paper in the house regularly?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 
Apart from the Dumfries Standard, and I think - my father used to get the Edinburgh evening News, or Edinburgh - evening paper. He used to get that. But that was all.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Did they get the {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Edinburgh{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
 papers delivered down here the same day?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Yes. They got the {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Glasgow{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
 ones. You got the Glasgow Evenings Times. That was a ha'penny. And they - they had an agent intown, it was a fellow, Godly - by name, and he was related to the Bendalls if you - I don't know whether you've ever heard the name of
 Bendalls the tin smiths. One of the girls married Jimmy Hilson if that means anything. The house factor. Well his wife was a Bendall. Well her uncle - used to be responsible for the reception and sale of the Times. They used to go down to the seven seven
teen train at night. And - get a parcel of evening papers. And he had probably about a dozen boys, around about the town selling the papers. And he controlled it all.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 They weren't sold in a shop?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Oh the shops were all shut, it was - half past seven - like before the papers arrived at the station.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 The boys would go round the street shouting?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Yes. Yes, up - up the town shouting.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 What about the other magazines, would you}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16396100\charrsid7372706 r}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid3852\charrsid7372706  sisters or your mother get any magazines to read?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 I can't remember ever seeing a magazine in the house.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Would your mother read the newspaper that came in?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 No - I think - anybody who - who was reading the papers or anything interesting it was mentioned in then.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Read out to everybody?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 And that was the end of it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Do you remember any funerals in the family?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Yes, I remembered my father's.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 You would just be nine at the time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 I was just nine at the time, I wasn't at the funeral. I was at the service but not at the funeral.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Did you have to get special clothes for it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 You didn't }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16396100\charrsid7372706 j}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 
ust wear your Sunday suit?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 No, a black suit. An black suit was bought.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 What about your older brothers and sisters, did they go to the funeral?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Oh yes. The - the boys were there. Were at the funeral.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 What about the girls?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Well they would be at the service in the house. The funeral service and - all at the service. But - only the - the men}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16396100\charrsid7372706 -}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 folks - were at the graveside.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 AND YOU would be too young?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 I was too young, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Who was at the funeral then, because you were short on relations round about weren't you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Yes. It - it would be - there was no - well there'd be neighbours. Neighbours at the funeral round about. But - no relatives beyond
 the - our family.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 The immediate family?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 
Mm hm. So that the pall bearers would be - would just be made up by neighbours. I don't know the rest of that, I don't know who was at the graveside you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Can you tell me a bit about your mother, 
when you're in a big family like that it must be very difficult to get really close to a person? Did you find she was an easy person to talk to? Or was she always busy?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 No. You - you never got near - your - your parents if you'd any trouble, you kept
 it to yourself. Not - that you were chased away but you were scared. That it might interfere with your freedom. If you said anything was happening I - I might be wrong in saying that but - that's the feeling I had, that you didn't bother your parents wit
h your troubles, you kept your troubles to yourself.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 What about your brothers and sisters then. Would you if you were in trouble go and ask them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Don't think so. I never - I maybe was lucky but I never really was in trouble. The only time I was i
n trouble I got a biff on the ear with a policeman fro playing with building material in-in the street. We were playing - they were repairing the streets at the time and I remember I was kind of the castle on the sand heap.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 And you were caught?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Aye, and - you know, just got a cuff on the ear, and it was right sore. But you wouldn't go back.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 How did you get on with the police? Did the policeman come round about the streets?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 They all were about the streets, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 And if they found small boys in trouble they could just give them a quick cuff?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 You got - that was right, you got a cuff and - that was the end of it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Were you scared for the police?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Oh yes. Mm hm, you were scared. You only had to get a cuff on the ear and -
 you watched your step in the future, you kept your own distance. I remember too talking about the policemen, I used to think it was very funny, they had a low two wheeled barrow. They used to go about the town at the pubs collecting all the drunks, put t
hem on the barrow and wheel them to the police station.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Is that the early black maria?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16396100\charrsid7372706 Well that would be the forerun}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 ner of the maria. But it was their own barrow.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 They were all helpless?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 All helpless, just layed on the barrow and they never moved. Wheeled along the - the - the cobbled streets.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 That would waken them up? If you had got into mischief would your mother ever threaten you with the police?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 No. No. No, she never - she never adopted that sort of - tactics, again - you m}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid16396100\charrsid7372706 i}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 
ght get a hiding from her. Like if you're doing something that she didn't approve of. And - you were challenged and you had to say why you were doing it. And if the explanation wasn't accepted then you got a walloping. Sent to bed. That was the punishm
ent.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 To go back to the policeman, how do you think he treated the folk generally?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 
Well - I don't think there would be - come involved in an argument. They laid down the law, what they said went. And you had to accept it at that. You couldn't argue with the policemen.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 But do you think they were quite reasonable in what they reckoned was the law?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 
Oh well - now that's a question. I don't know - my impression of the policeman was that he was there to maintain the peace. And he was given whatever power was required to do it. He simply acted on his own. You never heard of a policeman being reported.

\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Not like nowadays?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 No. Well I suppose - no, nothing like that, a policeman was a policeman. And he did his job and he maintained peace.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 And it seems to have been a reasonably peaceful town?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 
It was - it was, we never had any - trouble that I can - remember involving police. As I say I can always remember that incident, when I was kind of the castle. And got a rude awakening. B
ut if they did that nowadays they would be reported for hitting you.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 They're not supposed to lay a hand on you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 No, you got a }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16396100\charrsid7372706 wal}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 l
}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16396100\charrsid7372706 o}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 p on the ear. Mm hm.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 To go back to your own parents, you said you would get a hiding and sent to bed?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Mm hm.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Can you remember what sort of things you would get a hiding for?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 
Swearing. You heard a swear word outside. And you used it in the house and somebody heard you. Told - told my mother. Mother'd get hold of me. What was that you were doing. W
hat word was that you - you used? And - you say what you - the word that you've been using. Right, you come up the stairs. Upstairs you went and you got a walloping and put to bed.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Was it a wallop just with the hand?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Mm hm. Oh you had your trousers}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid929885\charrsid7372706  taken down and - she laid on. A}{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 ye, be as sore on her as what it was on me. Aye. That was the - that's the only time that she really - asserted her authority. If we're doing something that we shouldn't.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Can you think of anything else part from the swearing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 
No. No, well when we - we were out playing like that - there never was any trouble with - other kids or anything like that, running to the door and telling stories or - that never was done. And you would never become involved in fights, we didn't fight.

\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Did your mother ever tell you what to do if a child did hit you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 
No. OH she wouldn't - oh no, she wouldn't encourage you in that respect. She would rather have seen you getting a hiding. Than coming home, and - telling father what had happened.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 You hadn't to be a cly}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid929885\charrsid7372706 p}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 e?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Mm hm.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 How about the way you got on with your brothers and sisters? I mean some of your sisters were quite grown up when you were a school boy?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Did you have to treat them with the respect that you would give an adult?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Well - I don't know - we weren't cheeky - kids in the ordinary sense of the word. We weren't cheeky to our el}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid929885\charrsid7372706 d}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 ers, and - we kept on the good side of our elders, for the occasional penny that we got from them. You'd 
to watch your pees and qu's and if they wanted messages or anything like that well there was always a penny going.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Suppose grown ups were having a }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid929885\charrsid7372706 conversation}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 , would you be allowed to join in?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Well - we never were barred but I don't think it wa
s in us to interfere. If we heard a discussion going on and - we knew something I think we remained quiet until it was finished and then go to mother and tell her what we knew. But we would - we wouldn't interfere.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 You wouldn't butt in?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Would you say that you got your ideas about behaving from both your parents or from one more than the other?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 I don't think - I got any idea about behaving from my parents. Put it like that. You simply - carried on - as you - thought you should carry
 on. But - neither parent - ever interfered or told you - what you should be doing, unless as I say you did something wrong you got a hiding for it. You were put right then.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 But you never were given sort of special rules that you must never ever do so and so?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Or it was especially important that you always do something else?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 
Oh - well we - of course the - the usual place what was down by the river side and we were always warned now don't you go in the water. Keep out of the water. 
And of course - when you got to the waterside you never paid any attention to that. I have fallen in the river - the river - several times and went home - and got a walloping - for going into the river. We used to play down at the suspension bridge, where
 there was a ford across we used to play down there. If you were unlucky and slipped on a stone or something like that well it was just too bad.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 What about when it was flooded, would you be able to go near the river when it was in flood? Because that could have been dangerous.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Yes, well - you couldn't get out the house when it was flooded. See the flood water goes all round the whole - in 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Nith Place{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} from about - canna just wee shop, {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Richardsons{\*\xmlclose}
{\*\xmlclose} the cycle agents shop where it used to be. About half
 way up the hill. It flooded up as far as that. And then - if flooded up the High Street as far as - as beyond the pub, there's a pub there at the corner I don't know what they call it now, but if flooded there and it flooded over to 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Irish Street{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}. So that we were - we were up in the house.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 What happened when you were supposed to be going to school then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Oh well you had to wade out. The - my mother used to watch us from the window. And down we went an waded - we waded through the - water.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 It wouldn't be all that deep then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 No, probably about a foot deep. Deeper in the centre of course but round about the doors, our doors it would be - roughly about a foot deep.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 I suppose you would think it was great fun when you were a wee boy?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 
We didn't mind, no. But then we didn't get out in it, when we went home from the school - you was kept in, you're not going out there to play - all that flood water. And of course it was - our amusement where we just went to the window, the parlour windo
w and watched all the on goings of the folks and their difficulties, getting carried through and all that sort of thing.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Do you remember your father ever punishing you?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 No. Never.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Was it just mother's job?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Yes. Mother got the job. She - she really brought the family up.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Do you think she was a stronger character than your father maybe?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Well she run the house and I think the - she would feel that if she didn't - maintain a certain - amount of discipline the job might get beyo
nd her. And she asserted herself now and again, but - we were a very happy family.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 I suppose by the time it came to your arrival she'd had quite a bit of practise in discipline?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Mm hm. She - she had.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Did you think she would smack the girls as much as the boys?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Oh yes. Aye. She'd no compassion. Whoever was at fault got it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 When we were talking about schools?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Mm hm.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 And you said it was the toffs that went to the Academy?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Society is divided into different classes, can you tell me something about the class system in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Dumfries
{\*\xmlclose} when you were young?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Now what exactly are you after there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Well what sort of class would you say your family belonged to?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 We were working class - kids. And that was the m
ajority of the tupe of people that attended the board school. They were all working class kids.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 What about the others. What other class or classes were there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Well of course - there was - it was comprehensive. All the way up.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 I was thinking of the social classes, like the ones that went to the Academy, who would do that?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Ah that was the business folks. Their kids. Shop owners and business - owners.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 You say shop owners, do you mean just the ordinary wee shops?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Or the bigger shops?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 
The bigger shops. They were a cut above the - the wee shops. They - they were all reputed to be - earning bigger incomes. Whether they did or not - I don't know, but that was the general feeling. That they had a grocers shop or a butc
hers shop, they were better off financially than the - the working class kids.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 And say like Symons and Mac}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid929885\charrsid7372706  Don}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 ald, these sort of people?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Well neither Symons or MacDonald had any family.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 But that sort of type?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 They - oh yes. Ah well th
ey - they had - funds of their own. Apart from the earnings that they had - and they'd to be very very well off. I remember that the first world war, I shouldn't be saying it but it's a long long while back, MacDonald was the agent for - Lord Mansfield, w
ho owned the ground - on which Itchen Fort at Gretna was built.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 The ordnance place?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 The whole - aye, the whole of the {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Gretna{\*\xmlclose}
{\*\xmlclose} factory, and he was the agent in the sale and I think his commission was a half per cent, so you can imagine what his income was. That's the type of firm it was. It was good firm, we were in amongst the - landed gentry.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Would, you say there was a division between say your big shop owners and the landed gentry type?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Oh yes. Mm hm. When the landed gentry come in you
 were running to open the doors for them come into the shops and - or show them to a seat and - oh yes, there was no - beating about the bush if the landed gentry were there. They got all the service. That they could possibly get.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Where would teachers come in this scale do you think?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 
Don't know - teachers again - I think they were just reckoned to be employees. Working for their living just the same as the rest of us. But the shopkeeper, he didn't work, he had the business, and he employed shop a
ssistants to do the work. Therefore he was a cut - above the ordinary - employee.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 What about a doctor?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Well the doctors they were all landed - gentry class. They were all well off. Where they got their money from - as I said before I think - I 
think it was their wives that had the money. Certainly - Doctor Kerr, Murray Kerr was our family doctor, and I'm certain he would never - well we were a healthy family, but I'm certain he never rendered an account.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 How about the ministers?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 The m
inisters were - yes, well - the minister in those days, he came round - his - church members periodically, visited you all in the homes. He'd probably come in for - half an hour or so and sit and down and - get to know - all the ins and outs of the family
. What they were doing, and what prospects they had. Not - he - he really was interested in the family. But of course whenever the - the family knew the minister was in - they all made themselves }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid929885\charrsid7372706 scarce}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 . You know, upstairs out the road until the minister went out.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Would you feel he was in the same class as yourself?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 No. No, he was a cut above again. He was on a level - above us.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Would you think there was a class below your working class?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Well - I would think that the class really below we would be the - the tramps. Of which there was plenty in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname 
place}}Dumfries{\*\xmlclose}. Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 You mean sleeping rough?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 On they would - no - there was more}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid929885\charrsid7372706  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 lodging house. There was an awful lot of more lodging houses in the town. Yes. There was a - there was a bi
g lodging house, you know where the post office presently stands, well - that originally was known as King Street, it was a narrow street and on one side there was Booths restaurant, the other side was Murray}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid929885\charrsid7372706 \rquote }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 s pub. And {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Murray}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid929885\charrsid7372706 
{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}\rquote }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 s house was built over the - entrance to {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}King Street{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
. And you went up there, halfway up the street, turned left and through a close and you were at a huge board and lodging house.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 What sort of folk ended up in there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Well - they were - just I would say of the tramp class, h
ere today and gone tomorrow. No - no permanent abode, they just stayed in the board and lodging house. I think it was Gribbons lodging house they called it, but I can remember there was a big one there. Where that fraternity have all gone to I don't know 
but there are no more lodging houses now in the town but there was then.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 You said that even your employers jumped when the landed gentry came in?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Mm hm.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 When you were small were you ever taught to touch your cap or show respect in some way to people?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 You always touched your cap to the minister. Your schoolmaster. School teacher.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Anybody else?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 I - I think that was all. The minister and schoolteacher and the - headmaster.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Do you remember anybody ever touching their cap to your father or your mother?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 
Oh no. Oh no. No. No, you would never have dreamt of doing it to any of your neighbours. You would say hello or good morn - no, you didn't even say good morning. That wasn't a term that was used in those days. You never s
aid good morning or goodnight, it would be hello.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 You would acknowledge them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Yes. You wouldn't salute in any way. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 In the town who would you think were considered the most important people?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 The most important people I would say were the shopkeepers.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 All the shopkeepers together?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Yes, as a body. Shopkeepers.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Did they tend to be on the council and things like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Yes. Mm hm. They were actively engaged in the running of the town. Like the working man had no int
erest whatever. There was no Labour - Labour - lads in those days. Real - really known as Labour. There was just the two - Tory or Liberalism. But I - everything - it was the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid929885\charrsid7372706 \endash }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706  shop}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid929885\charrsid7372706 -}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 owners that really run the town in those days.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 You would say they were important than the top class?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 
The working man. Well the - the - the top class were all county. They were on the country councils outside the town. They - they weren't - they didn't live within the municipal boundaries. But - it was the shopkeepers.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Where you lived you say most of the people were working class, would they all have the same standard of living, or would there be variations?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Oh I think there'd be nothing to pick and choose.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 All much about the same?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Much - much of a muchness.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 You came from a big family?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Aye, well they were all more or less families of the same size.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 There weren't people that were very much poorer than you were?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 No. Well - again - round Irish Street, where the Mechanics Institut
e used to be - there was - houses, tenement houses in there - four or five - storeys high, and - they might - be termed - be determined - to be poorer - class working folks. But again that - they might - be more or less - be more Catholics in that communi
t
y. Aye. I can always remember one fellow that lived there. A fellow, Glendenith, it was a funny thing. He had a two wheeled barrow, a fine affair, with the legs on the barrow to stand it up. And the only time you saw that fellow working - was in the herri
ng season. Fish. When the fresh herring season come on - he used to parade through the town with a b}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid929885\charrsid7372706 it}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 
 of herring - oh his barrow, shouting, fresh herring. Fresh herring. And - the popular - story was that every time he said fresh herring, he said, God forgive me. Fresh herring, God forgive me. That was the story, we knew this kid.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Would you say }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid929885\charrsid7372706 that some families were thought}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid3852\charrsid7372706  of as rough and others as respectable?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Well curiously enough the only rough families that we - thought of as rough were the Catholics. Whe}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid929885\charrsid7372706 ther they thought we were rough}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706  I don't know. We always looked on the Catholics as a rougher crowd.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 But you didn't really mix with them to find out?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Oh no. You never mixed with them, no. No. You kept to yourself.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Do you thi
nk there was any one group that felt itself superior to the rest in the working class? Whether maybe a foreman in the mill, this sort of thing whether they might feel they were a bit above the rest?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Well where would - a for}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid929885\charrsid7372706 eman in the mill had very very }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 little standing. He probably got five shillings a week more than the workmen.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 You think there wasn't much difference?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 There - there was no difference no. The boss was there. At the mills. The boss was there, and he gave his orders to the for
eman. That was the end of it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Do you remember any sort of distinction between craftsmen and labourers then? Your father would be a craftsman?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 A craftsman. Yes. Everybody served their apprenticeship would be a - presumably be a craftsman. And the
n you had the labourers, well - the labourers again - they were more of the tramp frat - fraternity. They werena - weren't what you would say - residents of the town. They might have been but there was something wrong - with their career in their younger 
days when they didn't learn a trade.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 And they tended to go from job to job?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 
Mm hm. Although - I don't think there was the same dividing line between tradesmen and labourers. The tradesmen just - knuckled - worked in and just did the job, whether it was below his - dignity or not he did it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Was there not the same difference in pay scales between craftsmen and labourers in those days?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 There could have been very little - between it. As I said well - the farm labourer got his half crown a d
ay. And that tradesman he would probably get three and six a day, something like that. But there'd be very very little in it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Did your mother and father have the same attitude to people in different classes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Well - I never heard - I never did hear them express themselves. In any way. They just regarded - all their neighbours as one of themselves.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Thinking back to you touching your cap to the teacher and the minister?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Mm hm.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Would you mother maybe show respect to them in some way? That your father might not?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Well - I don't think - I think they were both the same. The same outlook.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Was it possible in those days to move from one class to another?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Well - I would say - not in your home town. You'd have to leave your ho
me town. If - if you wanted to be considered - a middle class or upper class. I don't think you would be looked up to in your own town - like you - you might have - started up a wee shop and - been successful. But I don't think the fraternity would have l
ooked on you - as being the upper class. Really.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 A case of a \{BLANK\} Returned his favour. \{BLANK\}
 And - it was a case of - work - he'd just working for his living just the same as us. Different altogether from the shopkeepers that were born in - to li
fe as shopkeepers. Or business gentlemen. They were all - looked up to. They wore their suits and the collar and tie, white collar and tie, whereas the - rest of the working class well - I suppose the - they hadn't the money to - to lay out on dress.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Do you remember anybody that went away and made a name for themselves? Moved up the social scale and came back?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Not - off hand. No, I don't think they would come back to {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Dumfries{\*\xmlclose}
, once they went away and got on they would stay away. There'd be sense of them coming back to Dumfries.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 How about moving in the opposite direction, do you remember anybody who started off in a higher social class and came down a way?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Well - even - I remember a - a certain - sweets merchant, he was in a good way of 
business and he went bankrupt. But even when he went bankrupt he was still regarded as one of the upper ten. Mm hm. And - they didn't deprive his widow of the - the house they stayed in, they owned it. And the widow was allowed to keep the home. Her house
. The creditors. The creditors did decide she had a family to bring up and they said, right, we'll leave her with the house.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Even without it being a limited company and so on?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Yes. Aye. No, I think once you were up and you fell down - the - the p
opulation didn't forget that you once were - one of the upper ten. You still were able to - maintain your status.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Just the same as the other way, if you pulled yourself up by the bootlaces, you were still regarded as down below?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 You were still - that was right, you were - you were still down on earth.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 They had long memories?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 
Well, everybody knew one another. Like you knew - you knew their history and - you would never - look on anybody that - was successful in business as - and become one of the upper ten as being in the upper ten. He was simply a working man that had got on.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Do you remember anybody being described as a real gentleman or a real lady?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 No, there were lots of - people that - they were real gentlemen, businessme
n like they were directors, what I recall directors down at the infirmary there. And it was amazing the good that these fellows did - carrying out their hob as director.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 You say they were businessmen?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 They were all businessmen and ministers. There was not - no working men on the board of directors. They were all businessmen.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 You didn't have the country?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Yes, the - the - the county gentle - they were in it too. But - they were all good people. On the job. That went out of their way to help.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 What about ladies?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Ladies.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Didn't you come in contact with any real ladies?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 
No. I don't know any - any ladies. It doesn't come back to mind probably - if I was - sitting down and thinking things over it might come back a bit. At 
the present I don't recall - any ladies. That were really looked on as good souls. They were simply - county - gentlemen and that was the end of it
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Was your house a rented one?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Or did your father own it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 No, it was a rented house. But I've no idea what the rent would be. It would be very little.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 
I was wondering what contact there was with the landlord, did he come and see to the property and made do any repairs that were needed, or did he just sort of collect the money every so often and that was that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 
I don't know who was the actual owner - of our house was. But I know other landlords used to go round - periodically and collect the rent, and they'd get a note then of any repairs that were needed to the building. But beyond that - no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 You weren't bothered with things needing being done and not bekng done?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 
No. Buildings were made to last in those days and didn't go wrong, and there was no - wanting destruction the same as there is nowadays. But you never had a broken window. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 I thought boys would have played football in those days too?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Ah, but you kept clear of the houses.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 So you don't really know about your landlord at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Don't know who the landlord was or what type he was or anything about him.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 
Do you remember feeling that your parents had to struggle to make ends meet? I suppose you've really got two sections of your life there, when you father was alive and then afterwards?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Mm hm. Well - when my father was alive, I think 
there was no - financial worries. They had sufficient to make the requirements. But after my father died of course - I think - money would be very very tight. That was the reason my mother had a - a lodger. To help the - eke things out, well - it was fift
een shillings a week that was his board. Full board for fifteen shillings a week. So you can guess what profit she made on him. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Before your father died was he ill or out of work?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 No, he died with pneumonia. Within a week - taking ill. Aye.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 What about getting help from the parish, that sort of thing, what was the opinion about that?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Oh - you never dreamt of going to the parish, in any event - they wouldna have looked - they wouldn't have considered your case at all.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Why was that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 
It was only the down and outs they looked at. The - there was the work house, have you heard of that, the work house. The work house - the work house - was originally where Cresswell is now. That was - that was the work house, and - elderly folks 
- well both men and women in it, but - with no home of their own, they lived in the work house and they had to -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 You say they had to work to help with their keep?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 That's right, the men - they - split wood into firewood bundles. And they went rou
nd with a great big two wheeled barrow, they were all two wheeled barrows in those days, and - it would stand about three or four feet high, and these bundles of wood were stacked in the barrow and there'd probably be four old men with that bag, and they 
went round the town, hawking bundles of firewood at a ha'penny a time.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 How were they looked on by the people?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 That was the work house.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 What sort of attitude would your family have to the people in the work house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Well, you just regarded them as paupers.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Did you feel sorry for them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 
No, you just accepted that was the way of life. And that they'd - they - they had a roof over their heads. And - they - they were working there under - and they were better done to there than they 
would have been had they not got into the work house. Being left outside to fend for themselves. But they were all elderly folks that were in the work house. There was no - yes, there was no - no young folks at all.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 So your mother would have to feel she was really on her beam end before she would have asked for help of any kind?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 You never thought of - parish relief it was called in those days. The social security.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 I believe you used to be able to get free dinners and suchlike?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Yes. There was a - a soup kitchen, up {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Loreburn Street
{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}. Now - I - there was a lady lived down there and I was talking to her about old {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Dumfries{\*\xmlclose} one day we got on about it. Her mother lived in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address
}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Loreburn Street{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}. And I said, yes, that would be up opposite the water wo
rks office. So she says, yes, and down the lane was the soup kitchen. Well the soup kitchen opened in the winter months. And - the poorer families, they used to send the youngsters along and they got jugs of soup for maybe a ha'penny or a penny.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 What would your mother have felt about that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 
Oh no. No, she wouldn't - she wouldn't - it would have been - below her dignity to go to the soup kitchen. That was - the feeling was that's only intended for the very poor. Like the soup kitchen was maintained
 by voluntary collections taken from time to time, in town. It wasn't provided by the authority. No, no. There was a committee of the soup kitchen, and period}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid929885\charrsid7372706 i}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 cally they made - appeals for money. And that kept the - them going. Of course it was only soup t
hat they dispensed. A big boiler filled with soup so that it wasn't a costly affair. But - there was quite a run on it in the wintertime.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 They didn't have anything in the summer?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 No, that's closed in the summer. That was the soup kitchen.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 But your mother was definitely not one for that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 
Oh no, she could - it wouldn't cost her that much to make soup for us. She would have the meat any - in any event. The soup with the meat would be used to make the soup, and then - eaten as the - second course.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 When things were hard after your father died you still had meat every day did you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Oh yes. So far - so far as -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 So whatever she cut down on it wasn't on food?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 No. So far as I - I - I can remember there was no difference. Ther
e was no difference at all. And - her rental then - it - questionable if she got ten shillings a week from the four girls, so that would be two pound. That was probably about her income. And she - she'd - yes - she would feed six or seven of us off that t
wo pounds.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Plus the lodger?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Plus the lodger's fifteen shillings a week.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 But she must have had a struggle?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Oh well, you'd no pennies to throw about.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 You think she was a good manager then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Mm hm. She must have been. We never 
were hungry. But - it was all plain feeding. And you got no more - there was no fancy cakes or anything like that. You got a bun once a week.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 You said that you were always fairly well dressed, you didn't get secondhand clothes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 No. No. Oh no, there was nobody to give us second hand clothes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Can you remember where you went for your clothes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 The Co-operative. The store. They had a drapers shop down the foot of the High Street. I - you know where - is it Morrell}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid929885\charrsid7372706 \rquote }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 s pub is, I'm trying to re
member any - shops - down there. Further down from Peter Drummond on the same side. Well - they had a shop there, that's where Ben McGovern worked, he was the - assistant there, he - you see Ben McGovern's letters often in the Standard, he had one in abou
t a fortnight ago. Well that's where he worked. In the - in the store drapery. And that's where our clothes were bought.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Did you get dividend in the store in those days?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Yes. Aye.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 You think that's one of the reasons that you went there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 It probably would.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 What about shoes, did they do shoes as well or did you have to go elsewhere for shoes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 I - I can't remember it - go to a shoe shop. They - the - the Co-operative, they had a shoe shop up in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address
}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Queensbury Square{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}. They' had a sho
e shop there. And - I know the girl - one of the girls that worked there was a - a girl Richardson, she married - a fellow Ballantyne and periodically you see his name - appear in the papers, he's now out in Canada, and - he's got on well and he's well up
 in the - in the Army, he was a Colonel or something or other. Colonel Ballantyne, and he married this - {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Richardson{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
 girl, I remember that. Out the shoe shop, she was in the shoe shop, so we must have gone to the Co-operative shoe shops for our shoes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Were you ever allowed to run barefoot?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Yes. You got your - boots and shoes off - at Easter, and you run all summer without boots or shoes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 What about going to school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 You went without them.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 You didn't wear shoes to go to school then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 No. No. You were - you took them off at Easter and that was your right for the season.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 It would be all right if there was a flood then.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Well oh aye, it - it wouldn't matter to us. That was the boys, I don't know - I don't know if the girls
 they went barefooted, but the boys went barefooted. We used to run behind the - water on the carts - when they went along the street laying the dust. They used to water the streets and we used to run after the sprinklers, and get our feet washed. I can r
emember that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 The soles of your feet must have been like leather you were done in summer?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Well there it is. Of course there was no tarmac. And the streets were all these - cobbles - sets. Aye.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Was it just when you started working that you started wearing shoes all the year?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 
Oh when you got on - when you got up - when you come round about the - ten year old, you didn't discard your shoes and stockings to the same - as you did in earlier years. Because you were sort of grown up then. You'
re past it, but - certainly as - kids - you can remember running behind the watering cart holding our trousers up and - getting the sprinkler sprinkling the water on our feet.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 They reckoned the summers were warmer in those days?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Well, as I - I s
aid - when I wrote my wee article into the Standard in the wagonettes - they've no protection, the passengers had no protection at all from the elements. Then when I began to think well - I can't really remember much rain - in the summer days.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 I think you only remember the good days?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 
Well - we seemed to be out playing every day. And we didn't wear raincoats, there wasn't such a thing as raincoats for the kids. It was be - before the day of the raincoat.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 I suppose the grown ups would have umbrellas?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 No, I don't think they had umbrellas, it was simply they wore an overcoat. But they - the grown ups - the men all had their walking sticks.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Was this a sign of being grown up when you had a walking stick?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 You got a walk - every - male - had a walking stick.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Did you have one?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Yes, I've got them there.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 How old would you be when you graduated to a walking stick then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Well - that - I'd be about seventeen or eighteen. When I became the - the owner of a walking stick.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 
That's round about when you were coming into the Army? When you were getting up to that stage, when you were having a walking stick to go out, were you interested in dress? Did you like to get yourself all poshed up to go out?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Oh well you were reaching the stage you had an interest in clothes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Round about sixteen?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Yes Seventeen. But then again you had no money to lash out yourself, you were dependent on what you could - become an heir to.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Could you tell me a bit about how got on in the Army, how did you like Army life?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 
Well - I got on all right. As I said, I - I - first of all - I bet they would do it nowadays, I paid my own train fare down to Carlisle to the interviews with recruiting officer of the Royal Flying Corps. Pai
d my own train fare. I saw the recruiting officer at Car - at {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Carlisle{\*\xmlclose}
, and in due course - I got - a calling up notice. And I'd be seventeen and a half then. That'd be 19 - 17. And - I had to report - to Galashiels I remember that. Had to go to Galashiels
 and sign on there, in the Army. And I would be posted on to the Royal Flying Corps. So from Galashiels - I went down to {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Hastings{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
. And there was a cadet school in the Royal Flying Corps - for - what - eight or - eight or nine months. And we did the cadet t
raining. Infantry training course and then cadet training lectures and all the rest of it. We used to have these daily and then ultimately I came back to - the - the Highland Light Infantry. Up in Wormit, {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Dundee
{\*\xmlclose}, come back there. And - I was too young - to be sent overseas. And I got a job as an officer's batman. Officer's batman.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 How did you like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Well - it suited me all right, I got - I forget how much I got - probably about five or six shillings a week as a batman.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Was that more than you would have got as an ordinary infantryman?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 
No - that was additional. Extra. As a batman. And - you had to be down at the officer's mess there first thing in the morning, about six o'clock in the morning - and clean the officer's uniform. And - 
you're just his manservant, after he went out you tidied up the room, made his bed and left everything all spick and span. And then you had to be back then again at - midday when he come in. If they wanted anything done you'd to be ready to do it, and aga
in at night when they came in. If he wanted anything done you would be there to do it. Now I was there until - the end of the year in 1918, after the armistice and then I was sent down to - {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Hamilton{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} to the pay office there.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Were you with one officer all the time as a batman?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Well you see the four officers. You'd three or four officers.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 How did you get on with them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 All right, I - I had a - I'd a grand officer, a - a - a Li}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid929885\charrsid7372706 e}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 utenant Arnold, I remember him. Aye and he was a Canadian and he
'd plenty of money and - he used to hand - hand out the tips lavishly. We got on well with him. Went over to Dundeed in the Sunday morning for his papers. That sort of thing, anything that he wanted - he just used to come and tell you - go and get me so a
nd so. You - you give him back the change, you got half of it to yourself. Oh, I - I was quite happy as a - a batman.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 I somehow had the feeling that officers would be a bit rough on their batmen?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Not in those days. No. They were all young officers. You see that was}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid929885\charrsid7372706  }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 in 1918, that was the commissioned - infantry man coming forward. They were all young fellows.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 The old soldiers had gone away?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 They were away. Aye. It was the youngsters stepping in to take their places. There - there was a {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}
Dumfries{\*\xmlclose} fellow, he was an officer name of Radcliffe, Jimmy Radcliffe, they had a bookies business in town. Radcliffe, well he was there. Oh I met quite a lot of {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Dumfries{\*\xmlclose}
 folks I met in the Army.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 How did you get on with your equals in the Army? Rather than your officers?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 
Well - I didn't see much of them because I was a batman. And I was away - well they were on parade, and I was in the mess, down at the officers mess and I only turned up at the barracks - at night and left in the morning, I wad s
own at the - officers mess all the day.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Wasn't there much social life connected with the barracks at night? Did the boys not all go out together to do things?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Well, I detested the small of beer, and I couldn't bear the smell of beer, there was a
 wet canteen, and that was where all the - the fun and games were done in the wet canteen. But - I couldn't stomach the smell of beer at the time. And I never was in the place. So I never was in the social life that respect. But there again you'd no money
 to spend. Your wage was sixpence a day.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Did you send money home to your mother when you were in the Army?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 An allotment, you had an allotment, you made an allotment of sixpence a day and the Army doubled it. That was sixpence a day and my mother 
got a shilling a day. And was left with sixpence a day.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 And she wouldn't have you to feed?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Oh no, she hadn't - she - it was a shilling a day that she got.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 It's not very much though?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 No, seven bob a week. And - I had - three and six a week for my pocket. So you couldn't go far on that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 What about warrants for getting home on leave?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Yes. You got periodic warrants. Aye. Bout once every - three months or something. You got two or three days leave.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Did you come back home to {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Dumfries{\*\xmlclose} for that?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Oh yes. Mm hm. Went down to {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Dumfries{\*\xmlclose} for my train fare.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 When did you come home on leave what sort of things did you do?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Oh now - well - I suppose I'd go back to the office and - have a chat with the other folks there. B
ut - there's none of the young - friends, you know, away in the army. You were just on your own.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 You didn't have a girlfriend to come back to?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Oh no. No. No, as I said, I'd no money for girls and therefore I didn't indulge. The first - first bus
 that I ever saw belonged to a fellow Craig. And it had solid tyres.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 That's the first motor bus?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 
Motor bus. And it had about a half a dozen rows of seats, and there was no side - there was a - a small - door, that you opened, but - you were clea
r - above the door. And there was no side to the bus, if it was wet weather they dropped a canvas screen. Now that was Craig's bus, and all the luggage went - all the goods and stuff that they carried went on the roof of the bus, and there you were, you -
 you sat in the - in the bus. Solid tyres.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 And the cobbles?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Aye. Right - well it - it run between the {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Carlton{\*\xmlclose} - I don't know who's in the 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Carlton{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} now, but the Carlton Restaurant and Bank End. There's where it ran. And that was the first omnibus.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 When would that be, were you just small at the time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Yes. It must have been - after the first world war. Just as small as that but thinking though even when I lived in 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Nith Place{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} it was the horse wagonettes that run up and down. But - Craig - he
 had the first motor omnibus, I can remember it was painted grey, and it had solid tyres. And - had side curtains, canvas curtains that they let down in wet weather.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid929885\charrsid7372706 What about the ho}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 rse buses, did you ever go in them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Oh yes. Aye. You got - a r
ide in the horse wagonettes. I think - if you knew anybody that was traveling you'd prob - practically got the - the ride for nothing. You went up a we stairway at the back of the wagonette, onto this big platform. And the seats were all faced - front bec
ause - no roof on the bus. No coverings of any sort provided. Hard wooden seats. And you sat there }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid929885\charrsid7372706 - and - the horses were general}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 
 galloped - down {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}St Michaels Street{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}, to get up steam to get up {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}
Irish Street{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} and then up onto the High Street.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 It would be noisy?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 
But - oh it was very noisy. And again I can remember the County Hotel, and the Kings Arms Hotel. They maintained as private - buses, horse buses, two horse buses. And they did nothing but run between the hotel and the railway station, bringin
g - bringing the travel}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid929885\charrsid7372706 l}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 ers back and forward - to the hotel. Now when you consider that - service provided by - hotel proprietors.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 When was the first time you ever went in a train?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Oh the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid929885\charrsid7372706 S}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 
unday school trip. Sunday school trip, that would be - probably about 1909 or 1910.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 It wasn't the done thing for people to go away on a train for the day somewhere?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 They - didn't get holidays. There was no monthly shopkeepers holidays or anything like that. I think - you'd get a - a day or two in the
 summertime but that was all.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 How about when you started working, did you get holidays being a white collar worker?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 I can't remember - oh I think we would. We'd probably get ten days or something like that. But - never went away. Never had a hol
iday. Really when I went off to the Army that was the really - the first time that I began to travel.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Begin to see life outside {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Dumfries{\*\xmlclose}?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Aye, I never never travelled before.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Would many people in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Dumfries{\*\xmlclose} travel?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Well they must have because there was a good train service, you could travel from Dumfries to {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Edinburgh{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} - on the old Caldonian line which is now closed. And you could travel to {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Glasgow{\*\xmlclose} and - the {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Glasgow{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} line. That was the Glasgow South Western Railway. And then you could travel up to Stranraer on the Port Patrick - railway. Port Patrick and Whittonshire railway. It run from 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Dumfries{\*\xmlclose} to Stranraer.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 And the trains were quite busy?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Oh yes. I - I remember too - there was an old fellow - talk - thinking about Duckett. This
 - there was a fellow McMurdo, he was the standard bearer in the Salvation army in those days. And he was what was known as a badge porter at the station. He wore a - a metal brass badge - is an armlet. And - he was the only porter that was allowed to wor
k on the platform of the station with passengers luggage. There was no other porter except the badge porter.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 I've never heard of that before?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Aye, that was McMurdo the badge porter. I can remember him fine and - he must have polished that brass 
badge religiously each day, it was always shining when it was on his arm.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 He }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid929885\charrsid7372706 must have taken a pride in his }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 ap}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid929885\charrsid7372706 p}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 earance then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Oh yes, aye. And how - how he managed to live I don't know, but - he would - he would be dependent on his tips.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Would he have a wage at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 
I don't think he got the wage. I don't think he got a wage. He was a badge porter, and - he apparently had the right to - attend to all the passengers baggage boarding or coming off the trains. And he loaded them up in barro
w and away he went. Aye, the two wheeled barrow was all the thing. These - buses, horse buses that went from the hotel to the station, the travellers arrived with a great big hampers, with all their ware in the hampers. And awaiting them at the hotel was 
t
he two wheeled barrows. And - the traveller would pick his bag - pick his man with the barrow, and - they'd hoist - they'd hoist the hamper onto the barrow, and - the traveller would tell the lad where to make for. And he was left to haul that big barrow 
w
ith the hamper on it, up - the High Street or wherever he was required to go round the shops, and whenever they got to the shops of course, off came the hamper and into the shop. It had to be loaded back up onto the barrow again. That was these big two wh
eeled barrows. You imagine -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 The stre}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid929885\charrsid7372706 e}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 
ts must have been quite busy in those days?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 
There was no - there was no speed. No. No, at - at the weekends with the carriers - carriers lorries from every wee village outside - there was a carrier that came 
into town with merchandise - he collected - he collected merchandise and took it back at the end of the day. And {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Queensbury Square{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
, that used to be a great place for the - for the me}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid929885\charrsid7372706 r}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 chandise lorries. All the stuff was taken up there and - dumped at the ca
rriers site 'til he came along later in the day, with his horse and lorry and picked it up and loaded it and away he went.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Did you ever go to the Root Fair when you were a laddie?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Of course. You went. You went for - days - the week before the R
oot Fair when the shows started to arrive, you went down there and - of course all the roundabouts, big roundabouts, they were hauled into position with ropes and - all the kids used to congregate down there. And help. And your reward that was on the open
ing Friday night of the fair yo}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid929885\charrsid7372706 u got free rides on the round}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 
abouts. Then of course as I said, David Miligan, he always had tickets - to distribute. And that gave you a free ride.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 What did you do for money for the rest of the time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Well you - you just -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Did you get some from your mother?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Yes. You cadged round about, you were always - wandering down there - }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid929885\charrsid7372706 t}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 rying to see a - a known face. On the off chance there'd be a penny or tuppence coming to you. But then the roundabouts were only a penny. The - the - the leap - the leapers that you }{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid929885\charrsid7372706 b}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 alled the smaller ones, they were a ha'penny. But the big one -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Is that the horses that went up and down?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Up and down, they were ha'penny, these leapers. Ha'penny. And every roundabout had its 
regular stands each year. They never varied their stances.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 They all knew exactly where they were going?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Yes. When you went down at - to the {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceName}}Dock{\*\xmlclose} 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceType}}Park{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}, the first roundabout - was one with gallopers. And he had - two long caravans, they were - Wil
mot had - family residence. And they were - sited just in front of Armstrong and Dicky's they did the water works. Well there was the gallopers first and then beyond that was the motors. Wilmots motors. On the opposite side was Greens motors. Then - there
 
was Days leapers. And then there was the steam boats. And then - beyond that was helter skelter, on the other side, and beyond that you got the shows. There was a Greens show, that was the first time we ever saw films. Greens show. And then there was the 
circuses, Pinders, Polars, and then there was Biddles Ghost Illusion show. They - they came with the - every year they had their stands booked every year.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 So you went and saw the same wonders every time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Oh yes, aye.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 How did they do for lights in those days?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 
They had their own - oil lamps. Aye. A long canister in which the oil was fed and it dropped down - the pipe and was lit - the other end, and it was hooked on.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Did they have as much music in those days as there is now?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Oh yes. Each round about had a great big organ. The organ -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 The organ that you turned the handle was it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 No, it - it was a handle, but they were all - manipulated by steam.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 You didn't get a job turning the handle?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Oh no. No, no. No. Ev
en at the circuses they all had their organ on the - stage in front of the - show. And you got a free show, you got - always got a free show before the - the show commenced, the circus, the actors and actresses came up and - display of dancing or - acroba
tics, something like that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 I suppose living in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Nith Place{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 We were right in the middle of it. Uh huh. But then you weren't out late because you'd no money.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 You very soon spent what you had to spend?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Mm. Oh you were rich if you had a sh
illing when you went down to the fair on the fair morning. A shilling. Twelve pennies if it was all in copper. You were rich, and it was all gone by dinnertime, but that shilling lasted you all morning. And that was your Root Fair over for another year.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Do you remember ever seeing the hiring fairs?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Yes. Not in the High Street, down - down in the Sands. Aye. There was - Johnson the horse dealer, and Walls the horse dealer, and - they had f
}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid929885\charrsid7372706 a}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 irs twice a year I think, in the spring and before the Roo
t Fair. The Wednesday before the Root Fair, and - they'd probably have anything up to a hundred horses, on show, and the farmers came in and - the horse was run up and down this street and if the farmer fancied it he bought it. And then round about you go
t the farmers - contacting their servants, and fixing them up for six - the next six months. That was all - in the - top part of the Sands.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 So they had the horses and the men at the same time?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Yes. It was - it was all done there on the Wednesday - the hiring fair.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Did you have a fair in the spring?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Yes. The March Fair. The March Fair.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Did you have shows then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Yes, not - not so big. No only about half the size. And it was more or less on the Sands, not on the Dock park. It was up on the Sands.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1003219 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 Did you get a holiday for that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2230984 JS  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3852\charrsid7372706 
No. Just for the Root Fair. The Saturday was the time for a laddie. You got the day off then. Oh, we must have had a week off from school because we were at the showground all the time - lending a hand wherever we were wanted.
